# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: demand-response
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:demand-response/demand-response] Utilities may signal demand requests to their customers in a variety of ways, including simple off-peak metering, in which power is cheaper at certain times of the day, and smart metering, in which explicit requests or changes in price can be communicated to customers.
[src:demand-response/demand-response] The customer may adjust power demand by postponing some tasks that require large amounts of electric power, or may decide to pay a higher price for their electricity.
[src:demand-response/demand-response] Some customers may switch part of their consumption to alternate sources, such as on-site solar panels and batteries.
[src:demand-response/demand-response] In many respects, demand response can be put simply as a technology-enabled economic rationing system for electric power supply.
[src:demand-response/demand-response] In demand response, voluntary rationing is accomplished by price incentives—offering lower net unit pricing in exchange for reduced power consumption in peak periods.
[src:demand-response/demand-response] The direct implication is that users of electric power capacity not reducing usage (load) during peak periods will pay "surge" unit prices, whether directly, or factored into general rates.
[src:demand-response/demand-response] Involuntary rationing, if employed, would be accomplished via rolling blackouts during peak load periods.
[src:demand-response/demand-response] Practically speaking, summer heat waves and winter deep freezes might be characterized by planned power outages for consumers and businesses if voluntary rationing via incentives fails to reduce load adequately to match total power supply.
[src:demand-response/demand-response] In 2013, it was expected that demand response programs will be designed to decrease electricity consumption or shift it from on-peak to off-peak periods depending on consumers' preferences and lifestyles.
[src:demand-response/demand-response] In 2016 demand response was defined as "a wide range of actions which can be taken at the customer side of the electricity meter in response to particular conditions within the electricity system such as peak period network congestion or high prices".
[src:demand-response/demand-response] In 2010, demand response was defined as a reduction in demand designed to reduce peak demand or avoid system emergencies.
[src:demand-response/demand-response] It can be a more cost-effective alternative than adding generation capabilities to meet the peak and occasional demand spikes.
[src:demand-response/demand-response] The underlying objective of DR is to actively engage customers in modifying their consumption in response to pricing signals.
[src:demand-response/demand-response] The goal is to reflect supply expectations through consumer price signals or controls and enable dynamic changes in consumption relative to price.
[src:demand-response/demand-response] In electricity grids, DR is similar to dynamic demand mechanisms to manage customer consumption of electricity in response to supply conditions, for example, having electricity customers reduce their consumption at critical times or in response to market prices.
[src:demand-response/demand-response] The difference is that demand response mechanisms respond to explicit requests to shut off, whereas dynamic demand devices passively shut off when stress in the grid is sensed.
[src:demand-response/demand-response] Demand response can involve actually curtailing power used or by starting on-site generation which may or may not be connected in parallel with the grid.
[src:demand-response/demand-response] This is a quite different concept from energy efficiency, which means using less power to perform the same tasks, on a continuous basis or whenever that task is performed.
[src:demand-response/demand-response] At the same time, demand response is a component of smart energy demand, which also includes energy efficiency, home and building energy management, distributed renewable resources, and electric vehicle charging.
[src:demand-response/demand-response] Current demand response schemes are implemented with large and small commercial as well as residential customers, often through the use of dedicated control systems to shed loads in response to a request by a utility or market price conditions.
[src:demand-response/demand-response] Services (lights, machines, air conditioning) are reduced according to a preplanned load prioritization scheme during the critical time frames.
[src:demand-response/demand-response] An alternative to load shedding is on-site generation of electricity to supplement the power grid.
[src:demand-response/demand-response] Under conditions of tight electricity supply, demand response can significantly decrease the peak price and, in general, electricity price volatility.
[src:demand-response/demand-response] Demand response is generally used to refer to mechanisms used to encourage consumers to reduce demand, thereby reducing the peak demand for electricity.
[src:demand-response/demand-response] Since electrical generation and transmission systems are generally sized to correspond to peak demand (plus margin for forecasting error and unforeseen events), lowering peak demand reduces overall plant and capital cost requirements.
[src:demand-response/demand-response] Depending on the configuration of generation capacity, however, demand response may also be used to increase demand (load) at times of high production and low demand.
[src:demand-response/demand-response] Some systems may thereby encourage energy storage to arbitrage between periods of low and high demand (or low and high prices).
[src:demand-response/demand-response] Bitcoin mining is an electricity intensive process to convert computer hardware infrastructure, software skills and electricity into electronic currency.
[src:demand-response/demand-response] Bitcoin mining is used to increase the demand during surplus hours by consuming cheaper power.
[src:demand-response/demand-response] There are three types of demand response - emergency demand response, economic demand response and ancillary services demand response.
[src:demand-response/demand-response] Emergency demand response is employed to avoid involuntary service interruptions during times of supply scarcity.
[src:demand-response/demand-response] Economic demand response is employed to allow electricity customers to curtail their consumption when the productivity or convenience of consuming that electricity is worth less to them than paying for the electricity.
[src:demand-response/demand-response] Ancillary services demand response consists of a number of specialty services that are needed to ensure the secure operation of the transmission grid and which have traditionally been provided by generators.
[src:demand-response/demand-response] In most electric power systems, some or all consumers pay a fixed price per unit of electricity independent of the cost of production at the time of consumption.
[src:demand-response/demand-response] The consumer price may be established by the government or a regulator, and typically represents an average cost per unit of production over a given timeframe (for example, a year).
[src:demand-response/demand-response] Consumption therefore is not sensitive to the cost of production in the short term (e.g. on an hourly basis).
[src:demand-response/demand-response] A pure economist might extrapolate the concept to hypothesize that consumers served under these fixed-rate tariffs are endowed with theoretical "call options" on electricity, though in reality, like any other business, the customer is simply buying what is on offer at the agreed price.
[src:demand-response/demand-response] A customer in a department store buying a $10 item at 9.00 am might notice 10 sales staff on the floor but only one occupied serving him or her, while at 3.00 pm the customer could buy the same $10 article and notice all 10 sales staff occupied.
[src:demand-response/demand-response] In virtually all power systems electricity is produced by generators that are dispatched in merit order, i.e., generators with the lowest marginal cost (lowest variable cost of production) are used first, followed by the next cheapest, etc., until the instantaneous electricity demand is satisfied.
[src:demand-response/demand-response] In most power systems the wholesale price of electricity will be equal to the marginal cost of the highest cost generator that is injecting energy, which will vary with the level of demand.
[src:demand-response/demand-response] Thus the variation in pricing can be significant: for example, in Ontario between August and September 2006, wholesale prices (in Canadian Dollars) paid to producers ranged from a peak of $318 per MW·h to a minimum of - (negative) $3.10 per MW·h.
[src:demand-response/demand-response] It is not unusual for the price to vary by a factor of two to five due to the daily demand cycle.
[src:demand-response/demand-response] A negative price indicates that producers were being charged to provide electricity to the grid (and consumers paying real-time pricing may have actually received a rebate for consuming electricity during this period).
[src:demand-response/demand-response] This generally occurs at night when demand falls to a level where all generators are operating at their minimum output levels and some of them must be shut down.
[src:demand-response/demand-response] The negative price is the inducement to bring about these shutdowns in a least-cost manner.
[src:demand-response/demand-response] The latter study found that even small shifts in peak demand would have a large effect on savings to consumers and avoided costs for additional peak capacity: a 1% shift in peak demand would result in savings of 3.9%, billions of dollars at the system level.
[src:demand-response/demand-response] An approximately 10% reduction in peak demand (achievable depending on the elasticity of demand) would result in systems savings of between $8 and $28 billion.
[src:demand-response/demand-response] While the net benefits would be significantly less than the claimed $35 billion, they would still be quite substantial.
[src:demand-response/demand-response] In Ontario, Canada, the Independent Electricity System Operator has noted that in 2006, peak demand exceeded 25,000 megawatts during only 32 system hours (less than 0.4% of the time), while maximum demand during the year was just over 27,000 megawatts.
[src:demand-response/demand-response] The ability to "shave" peak demand based on reliable commitments would therefore allow the province to reduce built capacity by approximately 2,000 megawatts.
[src:demand-response/demand-response] In an electricity grid, electricity consumption and production must balance at all times; any significant imbalance could cause grid instability or severe voltage fluctuations, and cause failures within the grid.
[src:demand-response/demand-response] Total generation capacity is therefore sized to correspond to total peak demand with some margin of error and allowance for contingencies (such as plants being off-line during peak demand periods).
[src:demand-response/demand-response] Operators will generally plan to use the least expensive generating capacity (in terms of marginal cost) at any given period, and use additional capacity from more expensive plants as demand increases.
[src:demand-response/demand-response] Demand response in most cases is targeted at reducing peak demand to reduce the risk of potential disturbances, avoid additional capital cost requirements for additional plants, and avoid use of more expensive or less efficient operating plants.
[src:demand-response/demand-response] Consumers of electricity will also pay higher prices if generation capacity is used from a higher-cost source of power generation.
[src:demand-response/demand-response] Demand response may also be used to increase demand during periods of high supply and low demand.
[src:demand-response/demand-response] Some types of generating plant must be run at close to full capacity (such as nuclear), while other types may produce at negligible marginal cost (such as wind and solar).
[src:demand-response/demand-response] Since there is usually limited capacity to store energy, demand response may attempt to increase load during these periods to maintain grid stability.
[src:demand-response/demand-response] For example, in the province of Ontario in September 2006, there was a short period of time when electricity prices were negative for certain users.
[src:demand-response/demand-response] Energy storage such as pumped-storage hydroelectricity is a way to increase load during periods of low demand for use during later periods.
[src:demand-response/demand-response] Use of demand response to increase load is less common, but may be necessary or efficient in systems where there are large amounts of generating capacity that cannot be easily cycled down.
[src:demand-response/demand-response] Some grids may use pricing mechanisms that are not real-time, but easier to implement (users pay higher prices during the day and lower prices at night, for example) to provide some of the benefits of the demand response mechanism with less demanding technological requirements.
[src:demand-response/demand-response] In the UK, Economy 7 and similar schemes that attempt to shift demand associated with electric heating to overnight off-peak periods have been in operation since the 1970s.
[src:demand-response/demand-response] More recently, in 2006 Ontario began implementing a "smart meter" program that implements "time-of-use" (TOU) pricing, which tiers pricing according to on-peak, mid-peak and off-peak schedules.
[src:demand-response/demand-response] During the winter, on-peak is defined as morning and early evening, mid-peak as midday to late afternoon, and off-peak as nighttime; during the summer, the on-peak and mid-peak periods are reversed, reflecting air conditioning as the driver of summer demand.
[src:demand-response/demand-response] As of May 1, 2015, most Ontario electrical utilities have completed converting all customers to "smart meter" time-of-use billing with on-peak rates about 200% and mid-peak rates about 150% of the off-peak rate per kWh.
[src:demand-response/demand-response] Australia has national standards for Demand Response (AS/NZS 4755 series), which has been implemented nationwide by electricity distributors for several decades, e.g. controlling storage water heaters, air conditioners and pool pumps.
[src:demand-response/demand-response] In 2016, how to manage electrical energy storage (e.g., batteries) has been added into the series of standards.
[src:demand-response/demand-response] Energy consumers need some incentive to respond to such a request from a demand response provider.
[src:demand-response/demand-response] Demand response incentives can be formal or informal.
[src:demand-response/demand-response] The utility might create a tariff-based incentive by passing along short-term increases in the price of electricity, or they might impose mandatory cutbacks during a heat wave for selected high-volume users, who are compensated for their participation.
[src:demand-response/demand-response] Other users may receive a rebate or other incentive based on firm commitments to reduce power during periods of high demand, sometimes referred to as *negawatts* (the term was coined by Amory Lovins in 1985).
[src:demand-response/demand-response] For example, California introduced its own ELRP, where upon an emergency declaration enrolled customers get a credit for lowering their electricity use ($1 per kWh in 2021, $2 in 2022).
[src:demand-response/demand-response] Commercial and industrial power users might impose load shedding on themselves, without a request from the utility.
[src:demand-response/demand-response] Some businesses generate their own power and wish to stay within their energy production capacity to avoid buying power from the grid.
[src:demand-response/demand-response] Some utilities have commercial tariff structures that set a customer's power costs for the month based on the customer's moment of highest use, or peak demand.
[src:demand-response/demand-response] This encourages users to flatten their demand for energy, known as energy demand management, which sometimes requires cutting back services temporarily.
[src:demand-response/demand-response] Smart metering has been implemented in some jurisdictions to provide real-time pricing for all types of users, as opposed to fixed-rate pricing throughout the demand period.
[src:demand-response/demand-response] In this application, users have a direct incentive to reduce their use at high-demand, high-price periods.
[src:demand-response/demand-response] Many users may not be able to effectively reduce their demand at various times, or the peak prices may be lower than the level required to induce a change in demand during short time periods (users have low price sensitivity, or elasticity of demand is low).
[src:demand-response/demand-response] Automated control systems exist, which, although effective, may be too expensive to be feasible for some applications.
[src:demand-response/demand-response] Smart grid applications improve the ability of electricity producers and consumers to communicate with one another and make decisions about how and when to produce and consume electrical power.
[src:demand-response/demand-response] This emerging technology will allow customers to shift from an event-based demand response where the utility requests the shedding of load, towards a more 24/7-based demand response where the customer sees incentives for controlling load all the time.
[src:demand-response/demand-response] Although this back-and-forth dialogue increases the opportunities for demand response, customers are still largely influenced by economic incentives and are reluctant to relinquish total control of their assets to utility companies.
[src:demand-response/demand-response] One advantage of a smart grid application is time-based pricing.
[src:demand-response/demand-response] Customers who traditionally pay a fixed rate for consumed energy (kWh) and requested peak load can set their threshold and adjust their usage to take advantage of fluctuating prices.
[src:demand-response/demand-response] This may require the use of an energy management system to control appliances and equipment and can involve economies of scale.
[src:demand-response/demand-response] Another advantage, mainly for large customers with generation, is being able to closely monitor, shift, and balance load in a way that allows the customer to save peak load and not only save on kWh and kW/month but be able to trade what they have saved in an energy market.
[src:demand-response/demand-response] Again, this involves sophisticated energy management systems, incentives, and a viable trading market.
[src:demand-response/demand-response] Smart grid applications increase the opportunities for demand response by providing real time data to producers and consumers, but the economic and environmental incentives remain the driving force behind the practice.
[src:demand-response/demand-response] One of the most important means of demand response in the future smart grids is electric vehicles.
[src:demand-response/demand-response] Aggregation of this new source of energy, which is also a new source of uncertainty in the electrical systems, is critical to preserving the stability and quality of smart grids, consequently, the electric vehicle parking lots can be considered a demand response aggregation entity.
[src:demand-response/demand-response] The modern power grid is making a transition from the traditional vertically integrated utility structures to distributed systems as it begins to integrate higher penetrations of renewable energy generation.
[src:demand-response/demand-response] These sources of energy are often diffusely distributed and intermittent by nature.
[src:demand-response/demand-response] These features introduce problems in grid stability and efficiency which lead to limitations on the amount of these resources which can be effectively added to the grid.
[src:demand-response/demand-response] In a traditional vertically integrated grid, energy is provided by utility generators which are able to respond to changes in demand.
[src:demand-response/demand-response] Generation output by renewable resources is governed by environmental conditions and is generally not able to respond to changes in demand.
[src:demand-response/demand-response] Responsive control over noncritical loads that are connected to the grid has been shown to be an effective strategy able to mitigate undesirable fluctuations introduced by these renewable resources.
[src:demand-response/demand-response] In this way instead of the generation responding to changes in demand, the demand responds to changes in generation.
[src:demand-response/demand-response] In order to implement demand response systems, coordination of large numbers of distributed resources through sensors, actuators, and communications protocols becomes necessary.
[src:demand-response/demand-response] To be effective, the devices need to be economical, robust, and yet still effective at managing their tasks of control.
[src:demand-response/demand-response] In addition, effective control requires a strong capability to coordinate large networks of devices, managing and optimizing these distributed systems from both an economic and a security standpoint.
[src:demand-response/demand-response] In addition, the increased presence of variable renewable generation drives a greater need for authorities to procure more ancillary services for grid balance.
[src:demand-response/demand-response] One of these services is contingency reserve, which is used to regulate the grid frequency in contingencies.
[src:demand-response/demand-response] As the ratio of inverter-based generation compared to conventional generation increases, the mechanical inertia used to stabilize frequency decreases.
[src:demand-response/demand-response] When coupled with the sensitivity of inverter-based generation to transient frequencies, the provision of ancillary services from other sources than generators becomes increasingly important.
[src:demand-response/demand-response] Technologies are available, and more are under development, to automate the process of demand response.
[src:demand-response/demand-response] Such technologies detect the need for load shedding, communicate the demand to participating users, automate load shedding, and verify compliance with demand-response programs.
[src:demand-response/demand-response] GridWise and EnergyWeb are two major federal initiatives in the United States to develop these technologies.
[src:demand-response/demand-response] Universities and private industry are also doing research and development in this arena.
[src:demand-response/demand-response] Scalable and comprehensive software solutions for DR enable business and industry growth.
[src:demand-response/demand-response] Some utilities are considering and testing automated systems connected to industrial, commercial and residential users that can reduce consumption at times of peak demand, essentially delaying draw marginally.
[src:demand-response/demand-response] Although the amount of demand delayed may be small, the implications for the grid (including financial) may be substantial, since system stability planning often involves building capacity for extreme peak demand events, plus a margin of safety in reserve.
[src:demand-response/demand-response] Such events may only occur a few times per year.
[src:demand-response/demand-response] The process may involve turning down or off certain appliances or sinks (and, when demand is unexpectedly low, potentially increasing usage).
[src:demand-response/demand-response] For example, heating may be turned down or air conditioning or refrigeration may be turned up (turning up to a higher temperature uses less electricity), delaying slightly the draw until a peak in usage has passed.
[src:demand-response/demand-response] Although this is an experimental program, at scale these solutions have the potential to reduce peak demand considerably.
[src:demand-response/demand-response] The success of such programs depends on the development of appropriate technology, a suitable pricing system for electricity, and the cost of the underlying technology.
[src:demand-response/demand-response] Bonneville Power experimented with direct-control technologies in Washington and Oregon residences, and found that the avoided transmission investment would justify the cost of the technology.
[src:demand-response/demand-response] Other methods to implementing demand response approach the issue of subtly reducing duty cycles rather than implementing thermostat setbacks.
[src:demand-response/demand-response] These can be implemented using customized building automation systems programming, or through swarm-logic methods coordinating multiple loads in a facility (e.g.
[src:demand-response/demand-response] Similar approach can be implemented for managing air conditioning peak demand in summer peak regions.
[src:demand-response/demand-response] Pre-cooling or maintaining slightly higher thermostat setting can help with the peak demand reduction.
[src:demand-response/demand-response] In 2008 it was announced that electric refrigerators will be sold in the UK sensing dynamic demand which will delay or advance the cooling cycle based on monitoring grid frequency but they are not readily available as of 2018.
[src:demand-response/demand-response] Industrial customers are also providing demand response.
[src:demand-response/demand-response] For example, Alcoa's Warrick Operation is participating in MISO as a qualified demand response resource, and the Trimet Aluminium uses its smelter as a short-term nega-battery.
[src:demand-response/demand-response] The selection of suitable industries for demand response provision is typically based on an assessment of the so-called value of lost load.
[src:demand-response/demand-response] Some data centers are located far apart for redundancy and can migrate loads between them, while also performing demand response.
[src:demand-response/demand-response] Shedding loads during peak demand is important because it reduces the need for new power plants.
[src:demand-response/demand-response] To respond to high peak demand, utilities build very capital-intensive power plants and lines.
[src:demand-response/demand-response] Peak demand happens just a few times a year, so those assets run at a mere fraction of their capacity.
[src:demand-response/demand-response] Electric users pay for this idle capacity through the prices they pay for electricity.
[src:demand-response/demand-response] According to the Demand Response Smart Grid Coalition, 10%–20% of electricity costs in the United States are due to peak demand during only 100 hours of the year.
[src:demand-response/demand-response] DR is a way for utilities to reduce the need for large capital expenditures, and thus keep rates lower overall; however, there is an economic limit to such reductions because consumers lose the productive or convenience value of the electricity not consumed.
[src:demand-response/demand-response] Thus, it is misleading to only look at the cost savings that demand response can produce without also considering what the consumer gives up in the process.
[src:demand-response/demand-response] It is estimated that a 5% lowering of demand would have resulted in a 50% price reduction during the peak hours of the California electricity crisis in 2000–2001.
[src:demand-response/demand-response] With consumers facing peak pricing and reducing their demand, the market should become more resilient to intentional withdrawal of offers from the supply side.
[src:demand-response/demand-response] Residential and commercial electricity use often vary drastically during the day, and demand response attempts to reduce the variability based on pricing signals.
[src:demand-response/demand-response] Electric systems and grids typically scale total potential production to meet projected peak demand (with sufficient spare capacity to deal with unanticipated events).
[src:demand-response/demand-response] By "smoothing" demand to reduce peaks, less investment in operational reserve will be required, and existing facilities will operate more frequently.
[src:demand-response/demand-response] In addition, significant peaks may only occur rarely, such as two or three times per year, requiring significant capital investments to meet infrequent events.
[src:demand-response/demand-response] The report estimates that in 2004 potential demand response capability equaled about 20,500 megawatts (MW), 3% of total U.S. peak demand, while actual delivered peak demand reduction was about 9,000 MW (1.3% of peak), leaving ample margin for improvement.
[src:demand-response/demand-response] It is further estimated that load management capability has fallen by 32% since 1996.
[src:demand-response/demand-response] Factors affecting this trend include fewer utilities offering load management services, declining enrollment in existing programs, the changing role and responsibility of utilities, and changing supply/demand balance.
[src:demand-response/demand-response] To encourage the use and implementation of demand response in the United States, the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission (FERC) issued Order No.
[src:demand-response/demand-response] 745 in March 2011, which requires a certain level of compensation for providers of economic demand response that participate in wholesale power markets.
[src:demand-response/demand-response] The order is highly controversial and has been opposed by a number of energy economists, including Professor William W.
[src:demand-response/demand-response] Hogan at Harvard University's Kennedy School.
[src:demand-response/demand-response] Professor Hogan asserts that the order overcompensates providers of demand response, thereby encouraging the curtailment of electricity whose economic value exceeds the cost of producing it.
[src:demand-response/demand-response] Professor Hogan further asserts that Order No.
[src:demand-response/demand-response] 745 is anticompetitive and amounts to "...an application of regulatory authority to enforce a buyer's cartel." Several affected parties, including the State of California, have filed suit in federal court challenging the legality of Order 745.
[src:demand-response/demand-response] A debate regarding the economic efficiency and fairness of Order 745 appeared in a series of articles published in The Electricity Journal.
[src:demand-response/demand-response] Circuit Court of Appeals vacated Order 745 in its entirety.
[src:demand-response/demand-response] Whether the Court of Appeals erred in holding that the rule issued by the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission is arbitrary and capricious.
[src:demand-response/demand-response] On January 25, 2016, the United States Supreme Court in a 6-2 decision in *FERC v.
[src:demand-response/demand-response] Electric Power Supply Ass'n* concluded that the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission acted within its authority to ensure "just and reasonable" rates in the wholesale energy market.
[src:demand-response/demand-response] 2222 on September 17, 2020, enabling distributed energy resources to participate in regional wholesale electricity markets.
[src:demand-response/demand-response] Market operators submitted initial compliance plans by early 2022.
[src:demand-response/demand-response] As of December 2009 National Grid had 2369 MW contracted to provide demand response, known as STOR, the demand side provides 839 MW (35%) from 89 sites.
[src:demand-response/demand-response] Of this 839 MW approximately 750 MW is back-up generation with the remaining being load reduction.
[src:demand-response/dynamic-demand-electric-power] Dynamic demand is similar to demand response mechanisms to manage domestic and industrial consumption of electricity in response to supply conditions, for example, having electricity customers reduce their consumption at critical times or in response to prices.
[src:demand-response/dynamic-demand-electric-power] The power utilities are able to predict to a reasonable accuracy (generally to within one or two percent) the demand pattern throughout any particular day.
[src:demand-response/dynamic-demand-electric-power] This means that the free market in electricity is able to schedule just enough base load in advance.
[src:demand-response/dynamic-demand-electric-power] Any remaining imbalance would then be due either to inaccuracies in the prediction, or unscheduled changes in supply (such as a power station fault) and/or demand.
[src:demand-response/dynamic-demand-electric-power] Such imbalances are removed by requesting generators to operate in so called *frequency response mode* (also called *frequency control mode*), altering their output continuously to keep the frequency near the required value.
[src:demand-response/dynamic-demand-electric-power] The grid frequency is a system-wide indicator of overall power imbalance.
[src:demand-response/dynamic-demand-electric-power] For example, it will drop if there is too much demand because generators will start to slow down slightly.
[src:demand-response/dynamic-demand-electric-power] A generator in frequency-response mode will, under nominal conditions, run at reduced output in order to maintain a buffer of spare capacity.
[src:demand-response/dynamic-demand-electric-power] It will then continually alter its output on a second-to-second basis to the needs of the grid with droop speed control.
[src:demand-response/dynamic-demand-electric-power] This spinning reserve is a significant expense to the power utilities as often fuel must be burned or potential power sales lost to maintain it.
[src:demand-response/dynamic-demand-electric-power] The kind of generation used for fast response is usually fossil fuel powered which produces emissions of between 0.48 and 1.3 tonnes of CO2 equivalent for every megawatt hour (MWh) generated.
[src:demand-response/dynamic-demand-electric-power] Thus, a significant environmental burden, in the form of increased greenhouse gas emissions, is associated with this imbalance.
[src:demand-response/dynamic-demand-electric-power] In principle, any appliance that operates to a duty cycle (such as industrial or domestic air conditioners, water heaters, heat pumps and refrigeration) could be used to provide a constant and reliable grid balancing service by timing their duty cycles in response to system load.
[src:demand-response/dynamic-demand-electric-power] Because it is possible to measure grid frequency from any power outlet on the grid, it is possible to design controllers for electrical appliances that detect any frequency imbalance in real time.
[src:demand-response/dynamic-demand-electric-power] Dynamic-demand enabled appliances would react to this same signal.
[src:demand-response/dynamic-demand-electric-power] When the frequency decreases they would be more likely to switch off, reducing the load on the grid and helping to restore the balance.
[src:demand-response/dynamic-demand-electric-power] When the frequency increases past the standard, they would be more likely to switch on, using up the excess power.
[src:demand-response/dynamic-demand-electric-power] Obviously, the controller must also ensure that at no point does the appliance stray out of its acceptable operating range.
[src:demand-response/dynamic-demand-electric-power] As line frequency is directly related to the speed of rotation of generators on the system, millions of such devices acting together would act like a huge, fast-reacting peaking power plant.
[src:demand-response/dynamic-demand-electric-power] The dynamic controller could also provide other ancillary services, such as aiding blackstart recovery—the ability of a power grid to be brought back to service after a power outage – if programmed with that function.
[src:demand-response/dynamic-demand-electric-power] Generally blackstarts are made more difficult because of the large number of reactive loads attempting to draw power simultaneously at start up when voltages are low.
[src:demand-response/dynamic-demand-electric-power] This causes huge overloads that trip local breakers delaying full system recovery.
[src:demand-response/dynamic-demand-electric-power] The dynamic controller could have these loads "wait their turn", as it were, until full power had been restored.
[src:demand-response/dynamic-demand-electric-power] Another vital balancing service is ‘fast reserve’ which is the use of standby plant to replace possible lost generation (e.g. due to a failed power generator or lost power line).
[src:demand-response/dynamic-demand-electric-power] By shedding load quickly while the running generators spin up, then switching back in to bring the frequency back to standard, dynamic controllers could spare the high cost of fast reserve generators.
[src:demand-response/dynamic-demand-electric-power] Also the fast response speed of this method would avoid possible brownouts occurring.
[src:demand-response/dynamic-demand-electric-power] The technology could also help facilitate greater use of generation from variable sources, like wind power.
[src:demand-response/dynamic-demand-electric-power] Demand-side techniques could be an efficient and cost-effective way to help integrate this resource onto the grid.
[src:demand-response/dynamic-demand-electric-power] In particular it would allow these sources to work in conjunction with virtual power reserves like municipal water towers to provide a reasonably predictable dispatchable capacity.
[src:demand-response/dynamic-demand-electric-power] Dynamic demand devices have the potential to save considerable amounts of energy by the services they provide.
[src:demand-response/dynamic-demand-electric-power] But before dynamic demand control can be widely incorporated regulation must be put in place to mandate installation on at least new appliances or an effective market mechanism must be created to reward installation of the technology fairly.
[src:demand-response/dynamic-demand-electric-power] One method contemplated is to enable the electricity meter that measures the electricity consumption also measure the grid frequency, and switch to a higher tariff if the frequency drops below a certain level.
[src:demand-response/dynamic-demand-electric-power] The monthly electricity bill will then say that so many hours (and so many kilowatt hours) were on the Regular tariff and a few hours on the Short Supply tariff.
[src:demand-response/dynamic-demand-electric-power] Those consumers without smart demand management have to pay the extra cost, but those who install smart technologies that adapt to the short supply periods will save money.
[src:demand-response/dynamic-demand-electric-power] On 1 March 2011, RLtec launched its Dynamic Demand frequency response service in hot water and HVAC load devices distributed across one of the UK's largest supermarket chains, Sainsbury's.
[src:demand-response/dynamic-demand-electric-power] This megawatt scale virtual power plant service provides commercial frequency regulating response to National Grid in the UK.
[src:demand-response/dynamic-demand-electric-power] Up to 5 GW of such diesel generation is used in France for similar purposes, but these technologies seem to be relatively unknown.
[src:demand-response/dynamic-demand-electric-power] There is no reason they should not be massively increased in scope to cope with even the intermittence introduced by wind power.
[src:demand-response/dynamic-demand-electric-power] In August 2007, the UK government published a report outlining what potential it sees for dynamic demand technology.
[src:demand-response/dynamic-demand-electric-power] The report stops short of recommending the government encourage its introduction.
[src:demand-response/dynamic-demand-electric-power] It lists a number of technical and economic barriers to its introduction and recommends these be investigated before the government encourage the use of dynamic demand.
[src:demand-response/dynamic-demand-electric-power] Dynamic demand is one element of a wider government investigation into technologies that can cut greenhouse gas emissions.
[src:demand-response/dynamic-demand-electric-power] However, in 2009 it was announced that domestic refrigerators are now being sold into the UK incorporating a dynamic load control system.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] An **electricity market** is a system that enables the exchange of electrical energy through an electrical grid.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] Historically, electricity has been primarily sold by companies that operate electric generators, purchased by electricity retailers, and sold to customers.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] The electric power industry began in the late 19th and early 20th centuries in the United States and United Kingdom.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] Throughout the 20th century, and up to the present, many countries have made changes to their system of supplying and/or purchasing electricity.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] Change has been driven by many factors, ranging from technological advances (on both the supply and demand side) to politics and ideology.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] Around the turn of the 21st century, several countries restructured their electric power industries, replacing the vertically integrated and tightly regulated **"traditional" electricity market** with market mechanisms for electricity generation, transmission, distribution, and/or retailing.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] The traditional and competitive market approaches loosely correspond to two visions of industry: the deregulation was transforming electricity from a public service (like sewerage) into a tradable good (like crude oil).
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] As of the 2020s, the traditional markets are still common in some regions, including large parts of the United States and Canada.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] In recent years, governments have reformed electricity markets to improve management of variable renewable energy and reduce greenhouse gas emissions.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] When electric power was first produced and sold to customers, it was not regulated by government.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] Customers would buy electricity from a producer, who would distribute it through their own network.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] However, the industry began to be regulated by a variety of government bodies.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] These diverse structures had a few unifying features: very little reliance on competitive markets, no formal wholesale markets, and customers unable to choose their suppliers.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] On the retail side, customers were charged fixed regulated prices that did not change with marginal costs, retail tariffs almost entirely relied on volumetric pricing (based on the meter readings recorded monthly), and fixed cost recovery was included into the per-kWh price.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] The traditional market arrangement was designed for the state of the electric industry common pre-restructuring (and still common in some regions, including large parts of the US and Canada).
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] Schmalensee calls this state *historical* (as opposed to post-restructuring *emerging* one).
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] In the historical regime almost all generation sources can be considered dispatchable (available on demand, unlike the emerging variable renewable energy).
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] Chile had become a pioneer in deregulation in the early 1980s (the law of 1982 had codified the changes that were started in 1979).
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] Only few years later the new market approach to electricity was formulated in the US, popularized in the influential work by Joskow and Schmalensee, "Markets for Power: An Analysis of Electrical Utility Deregulation" (1983).
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] At the same time in the UK, Energy Act of 1983 made provisions for common carriage in the electricity networks, enabling a choice of supplier for electricity boards and very large customers (analogous to "wheeling" in the US).
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] The incorporation of distributed energy resources (DERs) has inspired innovative electricity markets that emerge from a hierarchical deregulated market structure, such as local flexibility markets, with upstream aggregating entities representing multiple DERs (e.g., aggregators).
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] Flexibility Markets refer to the markets in which Distribution System Operators (DSOs) procure services from assets linked to their distribution system, aiming to guarantee the operational safety of the distribution network.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] This concept is relatively new, and its design is currently a subject of active research.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] In this sense, different entities can act as aggregators, e.g. demand response aggregators, community managers, electricity service providers, and more, depending on the characteristics of the set of assets being represented.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] The structure of an electricity market is quite complex.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] Markets often include mechanisms to manage a variety of relevant services alongside energy.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] A simple "energy-only" wholesale electricity market would only facilitate the sale of energy, without regard for other services that may support the system, and experienced problems once implemented alone.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] The competitive retail electricity markets were able to maintain their simple structure.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] In addition, for most major operators, there are markets for transmission rights and electricity derivatives such as electricity futures and options, which are actively traded.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] The market externality of greenhouse gas emissions is sometimes dealt with by carbon pricing.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] Electricity market is characterized by unique features that are atypical in the markets for commodities or consumption goods.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] The peculiarities of the electricity market make it fundamentally incomplete.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] Electricity is typically available on demand.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] In order to achieve this, the supply must match the demand very closely at any time despite the continuous variations of both (so called grid balancing).
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] Frequently, the only safety margins are the ones provided by the kinetic energy of the physically rotating machinery (synchronous generators and turbines).
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] If there is a mismatch between supply and demand the generators absorb extra energy by speeding up or produce more power by slowing down causing the utility frequency (either 50 or 60 hertz) to increase or decrease.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] However, the frequency cannot deviate too much from the target: many units of the electrical equipment can be destroyed by the out-of-bounds frequency and thus will automatically disconnect from the grid to protect themselves, potentially triggering a blackout.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] Electricity networks are natural monopolies, because it is not feasible to build multiple networks competing against one another.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] In order to address this, many electricity networks are regulated to address the risk of price gouging.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] A **wholesale electricity market**, also **power exchange** or **PX**, (or energy exchange especially if they also trade gas) is a system enabling purchases, through bids to buy; sales, through offers to sell.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] Bids and offers use supply and demand principles to set the price.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] Long-term contracts are similar to power purchase agreements and generally considered private bi-lateral transactions between counterparties.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] A wholesale electricity market exists when competing generators offer their electricity output to retailers.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] The retailers then re-price the electricity and take it to market.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] While wholesale pricing used to be the exclusive domain of large retail suppliers, increasingly markets like New England are beginning to open up to end-users.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] Large end-users seeking to cut out unnecessary overhead in their energy costs are beginning to recognize the advantages inherent in such a purchasing move.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] Consumers buying electricity directly from generators is a relatively recent phenomenon.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] For an economically efficient electricity wholesale market to flourish it is essential that a number of criteria are met, namely the existence of a coordinated spot market that has "bid-based, security-constrained, economic dispatch with nodal prices".
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] These criteria have been largely adopted in the US, Australia, New Zealand and Singapore.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] Wholesale transactions (bids and offers) in electricity are typically cleared and settled by the market operator or a special-purpose independent entity charged exclusively with that function.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] Market operators may or may not clear trades, but often require knowledge of the trade to maintain generation and load balance.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] Markets for electricity trade net generation output for a number of intervals usually in increments of 5, 15 and 60 minutes.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] In PAB, strategic bidding can lead producers to bid much higher than their true cost, because they will be dispatched as long as their bid is below the clearing price.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] In the absence of collusion, it is expected that MPS incentivizes producers to bid close to their short run marginal cost to avoid the risk of missing out altogether.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] MPS is also more transparent, as the new bidder already knows the market price and can estimate the profitability with his marginal cost, to do well with the PAB, the bidder needs information about other bids, too.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] Due to higher risks of the PAB, it gives an extra advantage to the large players that are better equipped to estimate the market and take the risk (for example, by gambling with a high bid for some of their units).
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] However, MPS results in producers being paid more than their bidding prices by design, leading to calls to replace it with PAB despite the incentive for strategic bidding.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] To handle all the constraints while keeping the system in balance, a central agency, the transmission system operator (TSO), is required to coordinate the unit commitment and economic dispatch.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] If the frequency falls outside a predetermined range the system operator will act to add or remove either generation or load.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] Unlike the real-time decisions that are necessarily centralized, the electricity market itself can be centralized or decentralized.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] In the centralized market the TSO decides which plant should run and how much is it supposed to produce way before the delivery (during the "spot market" phase, or day-ahead operation).
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] In a decentralized market the producer only commits to the delivery of electricity, but the means to do that are left to the producer itself (for example, it can enter the agreement with another producer to provide the actual energy).
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] Centralized markets make it easier to accommodate non-convexities, while the decentralized allow intra-day trading to correct the possibly suboptimal decisions made day-ahead, for example, accommodating improved weather forecasts for renewables.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] Due to the difference in the grid construction (US had weaker transmission networks), the design of wholesale markets in the US and Europe had diverged, even though initially the US was followed the European (decentralized) example.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] To accommodate the transmission network constraints centralized markets typically use locational marginal pricing (LMP) where each node has its own local market price (thus another name for the practice, nodal pricing).
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] This approach allows the operator to take into consideration the details of the configuration of the transmission system.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] The centralized market normally uses the LMP, and the dispatch goal is minimizing the total cost in each node (which in a large network count in hundreds or even thousands).
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] The centralized markets use some procedures resembling the vertically integrated electric utilities of the era before the deregulation, so the centralized markets are also called *integrated electricity markets*.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] Due to the centralized and detailed nature of the day-ahead dispatch, it stays feasible and cost-efficient at the time of delivery, unless some unexpected adverse events occur.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] Early decisions help to efficiently schedule the plants with the long ramp-up times.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] Price of a unit of electricity with LMP is based on the marginal cost, so the start-up and no-load costs are not included.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] Centralized markets therefore typically pay a compensation for these costs to the producer (so called *make-whole* or *uplift payments*), financed in some way by the market participants (and, ultimately, the consumers).
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] Market clearing algorithms are complex (some are NP-complete) and have to be executed in limited time (5–60 minutes).
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] The results are thus not necessarily optimal, are hard to replicate independently, and require the market participants to trust the operator (due to the complexity sometimes a decision by the algorithm to accept or reject the bid appears entirely arbitrary to the bidder).
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] If the transmission system operator owns the actual transmission network, it would be incentivized to profit by increasing the congestion rents.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] Thus in the US the operator typically does not own any capacity and is frequently called an independent system operator (ISO).
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] The higher degree of centralization of the market involves the direct cost calculations by the market operator (producers no longer submit bids).
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] A less-obvious issue is the tendency of market participants under these conditions to concentrate on investments in the peaker plants to the detriment of the baseload power.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] One of the advantages of the cost-based market is the relatively low cost to set it up.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] The cost-based approach is popular in Latin America: in addition to Chile, it is used in Bolivia, Peru, Brazil, and countries in Central America.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] A system operator performs an audit of parameters of each generator unit (including heat rate, minimum load, ramping speed, etc.) and estimates the direct marginal costs of its operation.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] Based on this information, an hour-by-hour dispatch schedule is put in place to minimize the total direct cost.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] In the process, the hourly shadow prices are obtained for each node that might be used to settle the market sales.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] Decentralized markets allow the generation companies to choose their own way to provide energy for their day-ahead bid (that specifies price and location).
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] The provider can use any unit at its disposal (so called "portfolio-based bidding") or even pay another company to deliver the energy.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] The market still has the central operator that exclusively controls the system in real-time, but with significantly diminished powers to intervene ahead of delivery (frequently just the ability to schedule the transmission network for day-ahead operation).
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] This arrangement makes operator's ownership of the transmission capacity less of an issue, and European countries, with the exception of UK, permit it (following the independent transmission system operator or ITSO model).
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] While some operators in Europe are involved in structuring the day-ahead and intra-day markets, the other ones are not.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] For example, the UK market after the New Electricity Trading Arrangements in UK and the market in New Zealand let the markets sort out all the frictions before real-time.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] This reliance on financial instruments leads to the additional names for the decentralized markets: **exchange-based**, **unbundled**, **bilateral**.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] To address this problem, various pricing schemes that lift the price above marginal cost and/or provide side-payments (uplifts) have been proposed.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] Liberopoulos and Andrianesis (2016) review and compare several of these schemes on the price, uplifts, and profits that each scheme generates.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] While in theory the LMP concepts are useful and not evidently subject to manipulation, in practice system operators have substantial discretion over LMP results through the ability to classify units as running in "out-of-merit dispatch", which are thereby excluded from the LMP calculation.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] In most systems, units that are dispatched to provide reactive power to support transmission grids are declared to be "out-of-merit" (even though these are typically the same units that are located in constrained areas and would otherwise result in scarcity signals).
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] System operators also normally bring units online to hold as "spinning-reserve" to protect against sudden outages or unexpectedly rapid ramps in demand, and declare them "out-of-merit".
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] The result is often a substantial reduction in clearing price at a time when increasing demand would otherwise result in escalating prices.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] The consequence is that prices paid to suppliers in the "market" are substantially below the levels required to stimulate new entry.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] The markets have therefore been useful in bringing efficiencies to short-term system operations and dispatch, but have been a failure in what was advertised as a principal benefit: stimulating suitable new investment where it is needed, when it is needed.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] In LMP markets, where constraints exist on a transmission network, there is a need for more expensive generation to be dispatched on the downstream side of the constraint.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] Prices on either side of the constraint separate giving rise to congestion pricing and constraint rentals.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] A constraint can be caused when a particular branch of a network reaches its thermal limit or when a potential overload will occur due to a contingent event (e.g., failure of a generator or transformer or a line outage) on another part of the network.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] The latter is referred to as a *security constraint*.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] Transmission systems are operated to allow for continuity of supply even if a contingent event, like the loss of a line, were to occur.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] This is known as a *security constrained system*.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] In most systems the algorithm used is a "DC" model rather than an "AC" model, so constraints and redispatch resulting from thermal limits are identified/predicted, but constraints and redispatch resulting from reactive power deficiencies are not.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] Some systems take marginal losses into account.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] The prices in the real-time market are determined by the LMP algorithm described above, balancing supply from available units.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] This process is carried out for each 5-minute, half-hour or hour (depending on the market) interval at each node on the transmission grid.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] The hypothetical redispatch calculation that determines the LMP must respect security constraints and the redispatch calculation must leave sufficient margin to maintain system stability in the event of an unplanned outage anywhere on the system.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] This results in a spot market with "bid-based, security-constrained, economic dispatch with nodal prices".
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] Many established markets do not employ nodal pricing, examples being the UK, EPEX SPOT (most European countries), and Nord Pool Spot (Nordic and Baltic countries).
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] Financial risk management is often a high priority for participants in deregulated electricity markets due to the substantial price and volume risks that the markets can exhibit.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] A consequence of the complexity of a wholesale electricity market can be extremely high price volatility at times of peak demand and supply shortages.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] The particular characteristics of this price risk are highly dependent on the physical fundamentals of the market such as the mix of types of generation plant and relationship between demand and weather patterns.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] Price risk can be manifest by price "spikes" which are hard to predict and price "steps" when the underlying fuel or plant position changes for long periods.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] Volume risk is often used to denote the phenomenon whereby electricity market participants have uncertain volumes or quantities of consumption or production.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] For example, a retailer is unable to accurately predict consumer demand for any particular hour more than a few days into the future and a producer is unable to predict the precise time that they will have plant outage or shortages of fuel.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] A compounding factor is also the common correlation between extreme price and volume events.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] For example, price spikes frequently occur when some producers have plant outages or when some consumers are in a period of peak consumption.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] The introduction of substantial amounts of intermittent power sources such as wind energy may affect market prices.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] Electricity retailers, who in aggregate buy from the wholesale market, and generators who in aggregate sell to the wholesale market, are exposed to these price and volume effects and to protect themselves from volatility, they will enter into "hedge contracts" with each other.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] The structure of these contracts varies by regional market due to different conventions and market structures.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] However, the two simplest and most common forms are simple fixed price forward contracts for physical delivery and contracts for differences where the parties agree a strike price for defined time periods.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] In the case of a contract for difference, if a resulting wholesale price index (as referenced in the contract) in any time period is higher than the "strike" price, the generator will refund the difference between the "strike" price and the actual price for that period.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] Similarly a retailer will refund the difference to the generator when the actual price is less than the "strike price".
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] The actual price index is sometimes referred to as the "spot" or "pool" price, depending on the market.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] Many other hedging arrangements, such as swing contracts, virtual bidding, financial transmission rights, call options and put options are traded in sophisticated electricity markets.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] In general they are designed to transfer financial risks between participants.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] Due to high gas prices because of the 2022 Russia–European Union gas dispute, in late 2022 the EU capped non-gas power prices at 180 euros per megawatt hour and the UK is considering price capping.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] Fossil fuels, especially gas, may be price capped higher than renewables, with revenue above the cap subsidizing some consumers, as in Turkey.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] Academic study of an earlier price cap in that market concluded that it reduced welfare, and another study said that an EU-wide price cap would risk "a never-ending spiral of higher import prices and higher subsidies".
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] It has been academically argued via game theory that a cap on the price of imported Russian gas (some of which is used to generate electricity) could be beneficial, however politically this is difficult.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] Rather than the traditional merit order based on cost, when there is excess generation ramping down the plants which most damage health has been suggested.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] Due to the growth of renewables and the 2021–2022 global energy crisis some countries are considering changing their electricity markets.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] For example, some Europeans suggest decoupling electricity prices from natural gas prices.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] A **retail electricity market** exists when end-use customers can choose their supplier from competing electricity retailers; one term used in the United States for this type of consumer choice is 'energy choice'.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] A separate issue for electricity markets is whether or not consumers face real-time pricing (prices based on the variable wholesale price) or a price that is set in some other way, such as average annual costs.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] In many markets, consumers do not pay based on the real-time price, and hence have no incentive to reduce demand at times of high (wholesale) prices or to shift their demand to other periods.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] Demand response may use pricing mechanisms or technical solutions to reduce peak demand.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] Generally, electricity retail reform follows from electricity wholesale reform.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] However, it is possible to have a single electricity generation company and still have retail competition.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] If a wholesale price can be established at a node on the transmission grid and the electricity quantities at that node can be reconciled, competition for retail customers within the distribution system beyond the node is possible.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] In the German market, for example, large, vertically integrated utilities compete with one another for customers on a more or less open grid.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] Although market structures vary, there are some common functions that an electricity retailer has to be able to perform, or enter into a contract for, to compete effectively.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] The two main areas of weakness have been risk management and billing.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] In the United States in 2001, California's flawed regulation of retail competition led to the California electricity crisis and left incumbent retailers subject to high spot prices but without the ability to hedge against these.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] In the UK a retailer, Independent Energy, with a large customer base went bust when it could not collect the money due from customers.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] Competitive retail needs open access to distribution and transmission wires.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] This in turn requires that prices must be set for both these services.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] They must also provide appropriate returns to the owners of the wires and encourage efficient location of power plants.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] There are two types of fees, the access fee and the regular fee.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] The access fee covers the cost of having and accessing the network of wires available, or the right to use the existing transmission and distribution network.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] The regular fee reflects the marginal cost of transferring electricity through the existing network of wires.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] New technology is available and has been piloted by the US Department of Energy that may be better suited to real-time market pricing.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] A potential use of event-driven SOA (service-oriented architecture) could be a virtual electricity market where home clothes dryers can bid on the price of the electricity they use in a real-time market pricing system.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] The real-time market price and control system could turn home electricity customers into active participants in managing the power grid and their monthly utility bills.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] Customers can set limits on how much they would pay for electricity to run a clothes dryer, for example, and electricity providers willing to transmit power at that price would be alerted over the grid and could sell the electricity to the dryer.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] On one side, consumer devices can bid for power based on how much the owner of the device were willing to pay, set ahead of time by the consumer.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] On the other side, suppliers can enter bids automatically from their electricity generators, based on how much it would cost to start up and run the generators.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] Further, the electricity suppliers could perform real-time market analysis to determine return-on-investment for optimizing profitability or reducing end-user cost of goods.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] The effects of a competitive retail electricity market are mixed across states, but generally appear to lower prices in states with high participation and raise prices in states that have little customer participation.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] Event-driven SOA software could allow homeowners to customize many different types of electricity devices found within their home to a desired level of comfort or economy.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] The event-driven software could also automatically respond to changing electricity prices, in as little as five-minute intervals.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] Comparisons between the traditional and competitive market designs experience have provide mixed results.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] Schmalensee concludes that it is plausible that the restructuring resulted in lower wholesale prices, at least in the US and the UK.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] Regarding resource adequacy, the US market at the start of restructuring had excess generating capacity, confirming the expectation that regulated prices provide an incentive for the generators to overinvest.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] In response, major transfer payments for capacity were instituted (in the US in 2018 the payments were getting as high as 47% of the new unit's revenue).
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] EU markets followed the American lead in the 2010s.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] Acceptance among residential customers in the US was minimal.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] Many regional markets have achieved some success, and the ongoing trend continues to be towards deregulation and introduction of competition.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] However, in 2000/2001 major failures such as the California electricity crisis and the Enron debacle caused a slow down in the pace of change and in some regions an increase in market regulation and reduction in competition.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] However, this trend is widely regarded as a temporary one against the longer-term trend towards more open and competitive markets.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] Notwithstanding the favorable light in which market solutions are viewed conceptually, the "missing money" problem has to date proved intractable.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] If electricity prices were to move to the levels needed to incentivize new merchant (i.e., market-based) transmission and generation, the costs to consumers would be politically difficult.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p01] The increase in annual costs to consumers in New England alone were calculated at $3 billion during the recent FERC hearings on the NEPOOL market structure.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p02] Since "energy-only markets have the potential to result in an equilibrium point for the market that is not consistent with what users and regulators want to see", all existing wholesale electricity markets rely on offer caps in some form.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p02] These caps prevent the suppliers from fully recovering their investment into the reserve capacity through the scarcity pricing, creating a missing money problem for generators.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p02] To avoid underinvestment into the generation and transmission capacity, all markets employ some kind of RA transfers.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p02] Typical regulator requires a retailer to purchase firm capacity for 110–120% of its annual peak power.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p02] The contracts are either bilateral (between the retailers and generator owners), or are traded on a centralized **capacity market** (the case, e.g., for the eastern USA grid).
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p02] The capacity mechanism is claimed to be a mechanism for subsiding coal in Turkey, and has been criticised by some economists, as they say it encourages strategic capacity withholding.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p02] It was designed to keep gas plants in the system.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p02] Unlike many other markets it is a hybrid system based partly on fixed costs and partly on market clearing price.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p02] Many say it is not good and should be changed, for example by using regional bidding zones because constraint management is the main problem in the market.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p02] The Capacity Market is a part of the British government's Electricity Market Reform package.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p02] According to the Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy "the Capacity Market will ensure security of electricity supply by providing a payment for reliable sources of capacity, alongside their electricity revenues, to ensure they deliver energy when needed.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p02] This will encourage the investment we need to replace older power stations and provide backup for more intermittent and inflexible low carbon generation sources".
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p02] Two Capacity Market Auctions are held each year.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p02] The T-4 auction buys capacity to be delivered in four years' time and the T-1 auction is a top-up auction held just ahead of each delivery year.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p02] Capacity Market Auction results have been published for several years.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p02] In the United States, regulators and regional transmission organizations have differing policies on whether there should be a capacity market at all, and how it should be structured.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p02] In 2008, three years after officially becoming a regional transmission organization, ISO New England held its first Forward Capacity Auction.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p02] In this design, a capacity auction was held three years prior to the "capacity commitment period", the year (reckoned from June 1 to May 31) in which the generator or demand-response resource was required to be available for dispatching.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p02] Prior to the auction, the ISO would determine the amount of capacity to be procured (the "installed capacity requirement"), and resources would have the opportunity to enter the market (if new) or leave it.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p02] The capacity auction follows a "descending clock" model: the price starts high and is reduced in successive rounds until a price is found below which insufficient resources are willing to sell to meet the requirement.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p02] All resources that clear in the auction are paid the same rate for their capacity.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p02] There were three annual reconfiguration auctions prior to the capacity commitment period, allowing resources to adjust their capacity offers for changing circumstances, and monthly reconfiguration auctions two months prior to delivery.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p02] Resources that received a capacity supply obligation were required to offer energy in the energy markets in amounts greater than or equal to their obligation, if physically possible, and could be fined for being unable to supply the committed capacity.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p02] One major consideration was whether to have a seasonal market, reflecting the facts that some resources have weather-dependent capacity and that the peak demand on the power system is different in summer and winter months.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p02] Another concern was preventing "phantom" resources — that is, generators that are planned to be built but have not demonstrated commercial operation — from influencing the capacity market, which in the old forward capacity market design required financial assurances from new resources.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p02] The changes leave PJM as the last remaining regional grid operator still using the three-year-ahead ("forward") capacity market structure.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p02] FERC accepted these tariff changes on March 30.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p02] The second tariff filing, implementing the seasonality and accreditation reforms, is expected to take place in the fourth quarter of calendar year 2026.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p02] The last forward capacity auction held under the old rules, for the June 1, 2027, to May 31, 2028 commitment period, took place on February 5, 2024, and procured 31,556 megawatts of capacity at a final clearing price of $3.58 per kilowatt-month.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p02] Within many electricity markets, there are specialised markets for the provision of frequency control and ancillary services (FCAS).
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p02] If the electricity system has supply (generation) in excess of electricity demand, at any instant, then the frequency will increase.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p02] By contrast, if there is insufficient supply of electricity to meet demand at any time then the system frequency will fall.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p02] If it falls too far, the power system will become unstable.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p02] Frequency control markets are in addition to, and separate from, the wholesale electricity pool market.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p02] These markets serve to incentivise the provision of frequency raise services or frequency lower services.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p02] Frequency raise involves rapid provision of extra electricity generation, so that supply and demand can be more closely matched.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p02] In the United States, seven Independent System Operators (ISOs) and Regional Transmission Organizations (RTOs) manage the transmission grid and facilitate wholesale electricity trading for over 60% of the country's power supply.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p02] These centrally-managed wholesale markets typically operate using a *two-settlement system*, consisting of a Day-Ahead Market (DAM) and a Real-Time Market (RTM), to coordinate the commitment and dispatch of generation resources.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p02] The day-ahead market allows market participants to secure prices and schedules for energy one day prior to the operating day.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p02] LSEs submit their demand bids and GenCos submit their supply offers for the upcoming operating day.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p02] The ISO solves a Security-Constrained Unit Commitment (SCUC) problem to determine the optimal "on/off" status of generating units and the dispatch levels that minimize total system costs while satisfying transmission constraints.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p02] The DAM produces hourly day-ahead Locational Marginal Prices (LMPs), which reflect the marginal cost of supplying the next unit of energy at a specific location.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p02] Following the close of the day-ahead market, ISOs typically perform a *Residual Unit Commitment* (RUC) or reliability check process.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p02] While the DAM clears based on financial bids and offers, the RUC process ensures that the system has sufficient physical capacity committed to meet the ISO's own centralized load forecast, which may differ from the bid-in demand cleared in the DAM.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p02] If the DAM schedule is insufficient to meet the reliability forecast, the ISO commits additional resources during this stage to ensure grid reliability.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p02] The real-time market (RTM) balances supply and demand during the actual operating day, accounting for deviations from the day-ahead schedule and unforeseen system conditions (e.g., generator outages or load fluctuations).
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p02] The ISO runs a security-constrained economic dispatch (SCED) algorithm, typically every 5 to 15 minutes, to determine the real-time dispatch instructions for generators.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p02] Financial settlement is based on deviations.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p02] Participants pay or are paid the real-time LMP for any quantity of energy consumed or produced that differs from their day-ahead schedule.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p02] In addition to energy, ISOs manage markets for ancillary services to maintain system frequency and stability.
[src:demand-response/electricity-market-p02] These services, such as regulation and operating reserves, are often co-optimized with energy in both the day-ahead and real-time markets to ensure the most efficient use of generation capacity.
[src:demand-response/load-management] Modern utility load management began about 1938, using ripple control.
[src:demand-response/load-management] By 1948 ripple control was a practical system in wide use.
[src:demand-response/load-management] Czechoslovakia first used ripple control in the 1950s.
[src:demand-response/load-management] Early transmitters were low power, compared to modern systems, only 50 kilovolt-amps.
[src:demand-response/load-management] They were rotating generators that fed a 1050 Hz signal into transformers attached to power distribution networks.
[src:demand-response/load-management] Early receivers were electromechanical relays.
[src:demand-response/load-management] Later, in the 1970s, transmitters with high-power semiconductors were used.
[src:demand-response/load-management] These are more reliable because they have no moving parts.
[src:demand-response/load-management] Modern Czech systems send a digital "telegram".
[src:demand-response/load-management] Each telegram takes about thirty seconds to send.
[src:demand-response/load-management] There are several formats, used in different districts.
[src:demand-response/load-management] In 1972, Theodore George "Ted" Paraskevakos, while working for Boeing in Huntsville, Alabama, developed a sensor monitoring system which used digital transmission for security, fire, and medical alarm systems as well as meter-reading capabilities for all utilities.
[src:demand-response/load-management] This technology was a spin-off of his patented automatic telephone line identification system, now known as caller ID.
[src:demand-response/load-management] In, 1974, Paraskevakos was awarded a U.S. patent for this technology.
[src:demand-response/load-management] At the request of the Alabama Power Company, Paraskevakos developed a load-management system along with automatic meter-reading technology.
[src:demand-response/load-management] In doing so, he utilized the ability of the system to monitor the speed of the watt power meter disc and, consequently, power consumption.
[src:demand-response/load-management] This information, along with the time of day, gave the power company the ability to instruct individual meters to manage water heater and air conditioning consumption in order to prevent peaks in usage during the high consumption portions of the day.
[src:demand-response/load-management] For this approach, Paraskevakos was awarded multiple patents.
[src:demand-response/load-management] Since electrical energy is a form of energy that cannot be effectively stored in bulk, it must be generated, distributed, and consumed immediately.
[src:demand-response/load-management] When the load on a system approaches the maximum generating capacity, network operators must either find additional supplies of energy or find ways to curtail the load, hence load management.
[src:demand-response/load-management] If they are unsuccessful, the system will become unstable and blackouts can occur.
[src:demand-response/load-management] Long-term load management planning may begin by building sophisticated models to describe the physical properties of the distribution network (i.e. topology, capacity, and other characteristics of the lines), as well as the load behavior.
[src:demand-response/load-management] The analysis may include scenarios that account for weather forecasts, the predicted impact of proposed load-shed commands, estimated time-to-repair for off-line equipment, and other factors.
[src:demand-response/load-management] The utilization of load management can help a power plant achieve a higher capacity factor, a measure of average capacity utilization.
[src:demand-response/load-management] Capacity factor is a measure of the output of a power plant compared to the maximum output it could produce.
[src:demand-response/load-management] Capacity factor is often defined as *the ratio of average load to capacity* or *the ratio of average load to peak load in a period of time*.
[src:demand-response/load-management] A higher load factor is advantageous because a power plant may be less efficient at low load factors, a high load factor means fixed costs are spread over more kWh of output (resulting in a lower price per unit of electricity), and a higher load factor means greater total output.
[src:demand-response/load-management] If the power load factor is affected by non-availability of fuel, maintenance shut-down, unplanned breakdown, or reduced demand (as consumption pattern fluctuate throughout the day), the generation has to be adjusted, since grid energy storage is often prohibitively expensive.
[src:demand-response/load-management] Smaller utilities that buy power instead of generating their own find that they can also benefit by installing a load control system.
[src:demand-response/load-management] The penalties they must pay to the energy provider for peak usage can be significantly reduced.
[src:demand-response/load-management] Many report that a load control system can pay for itself in a single season.
[src:demand-response/load-management] When the decision is made to curtail load, it is done so on the basis of system *reliability*.
[src:demand-response/load-management] The utility in a sense "owns the switch" and sheds loads only when the stability or reliability of the electrical distribution system is threatened.
[src:demand-response/load-management] The utility (being in the business of generating, transporting, and delivering electricity) will not disrupt their business process without due cause.
[src:demand-response/load-management] Load management, when done properly, is non-invasive, and imposes no hardship on the consumer.
[src:demand-response/load-management] The load should be shifted to off peak hours.
[src:demand-response/load-management] Demand response places the "on-off switch" in the hands of the consumer using devices such as a smart grid controlled load control switch.
[src:demand-response/load-management] While many residential consumers pay a flat rate for electricity year-round, the utility's costs actually vary constantly, depending on demand, the distribution network, and composition of the company's electricity generation portfolio.
[src:demand-response/load-management] In a free market, the wholesale price of energy varies widely throughout the day.
[src:demand-response/load-management] Demand response programs such as those enabled by smart grids attempt to incentivize the consumer to limit usage based upon *cost* concerns.
[src:demand-response/load-management] As costs rise during the day (as the system reaches peak capacity and more expensive peaking power plants are used), a free market economy should allow the price to rise.
[src:demand-response/load-management] A corresponding drop in demand for the commodity should meet a fall in price.
[src:demand-response/load-management] While this works for predictable shortages, many crises develop within seconds due to unforeseen equipment failures.
[src:demand-response/load-management] They must be resolved in the same time-frame in order to avoid a power blackout.
[src:demand-response/load-management] Many utilities who are interested in demand response have also expressed an interest in load control capability so that they might be able to operate the "on-off switch" before price updates could be published to the consumers.
[src:demand-response/load-management] The application of load control technology continues to grow today with the sale of both radio frequency and powerline communication based systems.
[src:demand-response/load-management] Certain types of smart meter systems can also serve as load control systems.
[src:demand-response/load-management] Charge control systems can prevent the recharging of electric vehicles during peak hours.
[src:demand-response/load-management] Vehicle-to-grid systems can return electricity from an electric vehicle's batteries to the utility, or they can throttle the recharging of the vehicle batteries to a slower rate.
[src:demand-response/load-management] Ripple control is a common form of load control, and is used in many countries around the world, including the United States, Australia, Czech Republic, New Zealand, the United Kingdom, Germany, the Netherlands, and South Africa.
[src:demand-response/load-management] Ripple control involves superimposing a higher-frequency signal (usually between 100 and 1600 Hz) onto the standard 50–60 Hz of the main power signal.
[src:demand-response/load-management] When receiver devices attached to non-essential residential or industrial loads receive this signal, they shut down the load until the signal is disabled or another frequency signal is received.
[src:demand-response/load-management] Early implementations of ripple control occurred during World War II in various parts of the world using a system that communicates over the electrical distribution system.
[src:demand-response/load-management] Early systems used rotating generators attached to distribution networks through transformers.
[src:demand-response/load-management] Ripple control systems are generally paired with a two- (or more) tiered pricing system, whereby electricity is more expensive during peak times (evenings) and cheaper during low-usage times (early morning).
[src:demand-response/load-management] Affected residential devices will vary by region, but may include residential electric hot-water heaters, air conditioners, pool pumps, or crop-irrigation pumps.
[src:demand-response/load-management] In a distribution network outfitted with load control, these devices are outfitted with communicating controllers that can run a program that limits the duty cycle of the equipment under control.
[src:demand-response/load-management] Consumers are usually rewarded for participating in the load control program by paying a reduced rate for energy.
[src:demand-response/load-management] Proper load management by the utility allows them to practice load shedding to avoid rolling blackouts and reduce costs.
[src:demand-response/load-management] Ripple Control is also used to turn off photovoltaic systems in case of electricity overproduction.
[src:demand-response/load-management] Ripple control can be unpopular because sometimes devices can fail to receive the signal to turn on comfort equipment, e.g. hot water heaters or baseboard electrical heaters.
[src:demand-response/load-management] Modern electronic receivers are more reliable than old electromechanical systems.
[src:demand-response/load-management] Also, some modern systems repeat the telegrams to turn on comfort devices.
[src:demand-response/load-management] Also, by popular demand, many ripple control receivers have a switch to force comfort devices on.
[src:demand-response/load-management] Modern ripple controls send a digital telegram, from 30 to 180 seconds long.
[src:demand-response/load-management] Originally these were received by electromechanical relays.
[src:demand-response/load-management] Now they are often received by microprocessors.
[src:demand-response/load-management] Many systems repeat telegrams to assure that comfort devices (e.g. water heaters) are turned on.
[src:demand-response/load-management] Since the broadcast frequencies are in the range of human hearing, they often vibrate wires, filament light-bulbs or transformers in an audible way.
[src:demand-response/load-management] The telegrams follow different standards in different areas.
[src:demand-response/load-management] For example, in the Czech Republic, different districts use "ZPA II 32S", "ZPA II 64S" and Versacom.
[src:demand-response/load-management] ZPA II 32S sends a 2.33 second on, a 2.99 second off, then 32 one-second pulses (either on or off), with an "off time" between each pulse of one second.
[src:demand-response/load-management] ZPA II 64S has a much shorter off time, permitting 64 pulses to be sent, or skipped.
[src:demand-response/load-management] Nearby regions use different frequencies or telegrams, to assure that telegrams operate only in the desired region.
[src:demand-response/load-management] The transformers that attach local grids to interties intentionally do not have the equipment (bridging capacitors) to pass ripple control signals into long-distance power lines.
[src:demand-response/load-management] Each data pulse of a telegram could double the number of commands, so that 32 pulses permit 2^32 distinct commands.
[src:demand-response/load-management] However, in practice, particular pulses are linked to particular types of device or service.
[src:demand-response/load-management] For example most ripple control systems have a telegram to set clocks in attached devices, e.g. to midnight.
[src:demand-response/load-management] Zellweger off-peak is one common brand of ripple control systems.
[src:demand-response/load-management] In recent years, radio-based load management (sometimes known as "**radio ripple control**") signalling systems have been introduced to replace traditional power wire ripple signalling systems.
[src:demand-response/load-management] Some radio-based load management systems have been criticised for lacking sufficient security measures, potentially compromising power grid security or allowing street lighting to be turned on or off.
[src:demand-response/load-management] Greater loads physically slow the rotors of a grid's synchronized generators.
[src:demand-response/load-management] This causes AC mains to have a slightly reduced frequency when a grid is heavily loaded.
[src:demand-response/load-management] The reduced frequency is immediately sensible across the entire grid.
[src:demand-response/load-management] Inexpensive local electronics can easily and precisely measure mains frequencies and turn off sheddable loads.
[src:demand-response/load-management] In some cases, this feature is nearly free, e.g. if the controlling equipment (such as an electric power meter, or the thermostat in an air-conditioning system) already has a microcontroller.
[src:demand-response/load-management] Most electronic electric power meters internally measure frequency, and require only demand control relays to turn off equipment.
[src:demand-response/load-management] In other equipment, often the only needed extra equipment is a resistor divider to sense the mains cycle and a schmitt trigger (a small integrated circuit) so the microcontrollers' digital input can sense a reliable fast digital edge.
[src:demand-response/load-management] A schmitt trigger is already standard equipment on many microcontrollers.
[src:demand-response/load-management] The main advantage over ripple control is greater customer convenience: Unreceived ripple control telegrams can cause a water heater to remain off, causing a cold shower.
[src:demand-response/load-management] Or, they can cause an airconditioner to remain off, resulting in a sweltering home.
[src:demand-response/load-management] In contrast, as the grid recovers, its frequency naturally rises to normal, so frequency-controlled load control automatically enables water heaters, air-conditioners and other comfort equipment.
[src:demand-response/load-management] The cost of equipment can be less, and there are no concerns about overlapping or unreached ripple control regions, mis-received codes, transmitter power, etc.
[src:demand-response/load-management] The main disadvantage compared to ripple control is a less fine-grained control.
[src:demand-response/load-management] For example, a grid authority has only a limited ability to select which loads are shed.
[src:demand-response/load-management] In controlled war-time economies, this can be a substantial disadvantage.
[src:demand-response/load-management] The system was invented in PNNL in the early 21st century, and has been shown to stabilize grids.
[src:demand-response/load-management] The largest residential load control system in the world is found in Florida and is managed by Florida Power and Light.
[src:demand-response/load-management] It utilizes 800,000 load control transponders (LCTs) and controls 1,000 MW of electrical power (2,000 MW in an emergency).
[src:demand-response/load-management] FPL has been able to avoid the construction of numerous new power plants due to their load management programs.
[src:demand-response/load-management] Since the 1950s, Australia and New Zealand have had a system of load management based on ripple control, allowing the electricity supply for domestic and commercial water storage heaters to be switched off and on, as well as allowing remote control of nightstore heaters and street lights.
[src:demand-response/load-management] Ripple injection equipment located within each local distribution network signals to ripple control receivers at the customer's premises.
[src:demand-response/load-management] Control may either done manually by the local distribution network company in response to local outages or requests to reduce demand from the transmission system operator (i.e.
[src:demand-response/load-management] Transpower), or automatically when injection equipment detects mains frequency falling below 49.2 Hz.
[src:demand-response/load-management] Ripple control receivers are assigned to one of several ripple channels to allow the network company to only turn off supply on part of the network, and to allow staged restoration of supply to reduce the impact of a surge in demand when power is restored to water heaters after a period of time off.
[src:demand-response/load-management] Depending on the area, the consumer may have two electricity meters, one for normal supply ("Anytime") and one for the load-managed supply ("Controlled"), with Controlled supply billed at a lower rate per kilowatt-hour than Anytime supply.
[src:demand-response/load-management] For those with load-managed supply but only a single meter, electricity is billed at the "Composite" rate, priced between Anytime and Controlled.
[src:demand-response/load-management] The Czechs have operated ripple control systems since the 1950s.
[src:demand-response/load-management] France has an EJP tariff, which allows it to disconnect certain loads and to encourage consumers to disconnect certain loads.
[src:demand-response/load-management] This tariff is no longer available for new clients (as of July 2009).
[src:demand-response/load-management] The *Tempo* tariff also includes different types of days with different prices, but has been discontinued for new clients as well (as of July 2009).
[src:demand-response/load-management] Reduced prices during nighttime are available for customers for a higher monthly fee.
[src:demand-response/load-management] The distribution system operator Westnetz and gridX piloted a load management solution.
[src:demand-response/load-management] The solution enables the grid operator to communicate with local energy management systems and adjust the available load for EV charging in response to the state of the grid.
[src:demand-response/load-management] Rltec in the UK in 2009 reported that domestic refrigerators are being sold fitted with their dynamic load response systems.
[src:demand-response/load-management] In 2011 it was announced that the Sainsbury supermarket chain will use dynamic demand technology on their heating and ventilation equipment.
[src:demand-response/load-management] In the UK, night storage heaters are often used with a time-switched off-peak supply option - Economy 7 or Economy 10.
[src:demand-response/load-management] There is also a programme that allows industrial loads to be disconnected using circuit breakers triggered automatically by frequency sensitive relays fitted on site.
[src:demand-response/load-management] This operates in conjunction with Standing Reserve, a programme using diesel generators.
[src:demand-response/load-management] These can also be remotely switched using BBC Radio 4 Longwave Radio teleswitch.
[src:demand-response/load-management] SP transmission deployed Dynamic Load Management scheme in Dumfries and Galloway area using real time monitoring of embedded generation and disconnecting them, should an overload be detected on the transmission Network.
[src:demand-response/peak-demand] Some utilities will charge customers based on their individual peak demand.
[src:demand-response/peak-demand] The highest demand during each month or even a single 15 to 30 minute period of highest use in the previous year may be used to calculate charges.
[src:demand-response/peak-demand] The renewable energy transition will include considerations for peak demand.
[src:demand-response/peak-demand] Electricity network is built to deal with the highest possible peak demand otherwise blackout may happen.
[src:demand-response/peak-demand] In Australia, demand tariff has three components: peak demand charge, energy charge and daily connection charge.
[src:demand-response/peak-demand] For example, for large customers (commercial, industrial or mixed of commercial/residential), the peak demand charge is based on the highest 30 minutes electricity consumption in a month; the energy charge is based on a month electricity consumption.
[src:demand-response/peak-demand] This type of demand tariff is gradually introduced to residential households and will be rolled out by 2020 in Queensland Australia.
[src:demand-response/peak-demand] How to manage electricity bills under demand tariff can be challenging.
[src:demand-response/peak-demand] The key solutions involve improving building efficiency and managing the operational settings of large power appliances.
[src:demand-response/peak-demand] Peak Demand depends on the demography, the economy, the weather, the climate, the season, the day of the week and other factors.
[src:demand-response/peak-demand] In industrialised regions of China or Germany, the peak demands mostly occur in day time.
[src:demand-response/peak-demand] However, in more service based economy such as Australia, the daily peak demands often occur in the late afternoon to early evening time (e.g.
[src:demand-response/peak-demand] Residential and commercial electricity demand contributes a lot to this type of network peak demand.
[src:demand-response/peak-demand] Peak demand is considered to be the opposite to off-peak hours when power demand is usually low.
[src:demand-response/peak-demand] Sometimes, there are 3 time-of-use zones: peak, shoulder and offpeak.
[src:demand-response/peak-demand] Shoulder is often the time between peak and offpeak in weekdays.
[src:demand-response/peak-demand] Weekends are often just peak and offpeak in terms of managing electricity loads for the network.
[src:demand-response/peak-demand] Peak demand may exceed the maximum supply levels that the electrical power industry can generate, resulting in power outages and load shedding.
[src:demand-response/peak-demand] This often occurs during heat waves when use of air conditioners and powered fans raises the rate of energy consumption significantly.
[src:demand-response/peak-demand] During a shortage authorities may request the public to curtail their energy use and shift it to a non-peak period.
[src:demand-response/peak-demand] Power stations specifically constructed for providing power to electrical grids for peak demand are called peaking power plants or 'peakers'.
[src:demand-response/peak-demand] In general, Natural gas fueled power stations can be fired up rapidly and are therefore often utilized at peak demand times.
[src:demand-response/peak-demand] Combined cycle power plants can frequently provide power for peak demand, as well as run efficiently for baseload power.
[src:demand-response/peak-demand] Hydroelectric power and pumped storage type dams such as Carters Dam in the U.S. state of Georgia help to meet peak demand as well.
[src:demand-response/peak-demand] The chances that a wind farm will be unable to meet peak demand are greater than for a fossil-fueled power station, due to the ability to store liquid fuels for use during peak demand.
[src:demand-response/peak-demand] Solar power's peak output often naturally coincides with daytime peaks of usage due to air conditioning.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p01] The **smart grid** is an enhancement of the 20th century electrical grid, using two-way communications and distributed so-called intelligent devices.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p01] Two-way flows of electricity and information could improve the delivery network.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p01] Research is mainly focused on three systems of a smart grid – the infrastructure system, the management system, and the protection system.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p01] Electronic power conditioning and control of the production and distribution of electricity are important aspects of the smart grid.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p01] The smart grid represents the full suite of current and proposed responses to the challenges of electricity supply.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p01] Numerous contributions to the overall improvement of energy infrastructure efficiency are anticipated from the deployment of smart grid technology, in particular including demand-side management.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p01] The improved flexibility of the smart grid permits greater penetration of highly variable renewable energy sources such as solar power and wind power, even without the addition of energy storage.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p01] Smart grids could also monitor/control residential devices that are noncritical during periods of peak power consumption, and return their function during nonpeak hours.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p01] Concerns with smart grid technology mostly focus on smart meters, items enabled by them, and general security issues.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p01] Roll-out of smart grid technology also implies a fundamental re-engineering of the electricity services industry, although typical usage of the term is focused on the technical infrastructure.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p01] Smart grid policy is organized in Europe as Smart Grid European Technology Platform.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p01] Policy in the United States is described in Title 42 of the United States Code.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p01] Smart grids are not to be confused with sector coupled smart energy systems, as smart grids primarily refers to the power sector, while smart energy system use an integrated holistic focus which also includes other sectors of the energy system with the intent to create synergies between them.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p01] The first alternating current power grid system was installed in 1886 in Great Barrington, Massachusetts.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p01] At that time, the grid was a centralized unidirectional system of electric power transmission, electricity distribution, and demand-driven control.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p01] In the 20th century, local grids grew over time and were eventually interconnected for economic and reliability reasons.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p01] Power stations were located strategically to be close to fossil fuel reserves (either the mines or wells themselves or else close to rail, road, or port supply lines).
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p01] Siting of hydroelectric dams in mountain areas also strongly influenced the structure of the emerging grid.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p01] Nuclear power plants were sited for the availability of cooling water.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p01] Finally, fossil fuel-fired power stations were initially very polluting and were sited as far as economically possible from population centres once electricity distribution networks permitted it.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p01] By the late 1960s, the electricity grid reached the overwhelming majority of the population of developed countries, with only outlying regional areas remaining 'off-grid'.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p01] Metering of electricity consumption was necessary on a per-user basis in order to allow appropriate billing according to the (highly variable) level of consumption of different users.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p01] Because of limited data collection and processing capability during the period of growth of the grid, fixed-tariff arrangements were commonly put in place, as well as dual-tariff arrangements where night-time power was charged at a lower rate than daytime power.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p01] The motivation for dual-tariff arrangements was the lower night-time demand.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p01] The metering capabilities of the 1960s grid meant technological limitations on the degree to which price signals could be propagated through the system.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p01] From the 1970s to the 1990s, growing demand led to increasing numbers of power stations.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p01] In some areas, the supply of electricity, especially at peak times, could not keep up with this demand, resulting in poor power quality including blackouts, power cuts, and brownouts.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p01] Increasingly, electricity was depended on for industry, heating, communication, lighting, and entertainment, and consumers demanded ever-higher levels of reliability.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p01] Towards the end of the 20th century, electricity demand patterns were established: domestic heating and air-conditioning led to daily peaks in demand that were met by an array of 'peaking power generators' that would only be turned on for short periods each day.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p01] In the 21st century, some developing countries like China, India, and Brazil were seen as pioneers of smart grid deployment.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p01] Since the early 21st century, opportunities to take advantage of improvements in electronic communication technology to resolve the limitations and costs of the electrical grid have become apparent.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p01] Technological limitations on metering no longer force peak power prices to be averaged out and passed on to all consumers equally.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p01] In parallel, growing concerns over environmental damage from fossil-fired power stations have led to a desire to use large amounts of renewable energy.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p01] Dominant forms such as wind power and solar power are highly variable, and so the need for more sophisticated control systems became apparent, to facilitate the connection of sources to the otherwise highly controllable grid.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p01] Power from photovoltaic cells (and to lesser extent wind turbines) has also, significantly, called into question the imperative for large, centralised power stations.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p01] The rapidly falling costs point to a major change from the centralised grid topology to one that is highly distributed, with power being both generated *and* consumed right at the limits of the grid.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p01] Finally, growing concern over terrorist attacks in some countries has led to calls for a more robust energy grid that is less dependent on centralised power stations that were perceived to be potential attack targets.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p01] The first official definition of Smart Grid was provided by the Energy Independence and Security Act of 2007 (EISA-2007), which was approved by the US Congress in January 2007, and signed to law by President George W.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p01] That definition was used in the European Commission Communication (2011) 202.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p01] A common element to most definitions is the application of digital processing and communications to the power grid, making data flow and information management central to the smart grid.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p01] Various capabilities result from the deeply integrated use of digital technology with power grids.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p01] Integration of the new grid information is one of the key issues in the design of smart grids.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p01] Much of the work that has been going on in electric grid modernization, especially substation and distribution automation, is now included in the general concept of the smart grid.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p01] Smart grid technologies emerged from earlier attempts at using electronic control, metering, and monitoring.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p01] In the 1980s, automatic meter reading was used for monitoring loads from large customers and evolved into the Advanced Metering Infrastructure of the 1990s, whose meters could store how electricity was used at different times of the day.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p01] Smart meters add continuous communications so that monitoring can be done in real-time, and can be used as a gateway to demand response-aware devices and "smart sockets" in the home.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p01] Early forms of such demand side management technologies were dynamic demand aware devices that passively sensed the load on the grid by monitoring changes in the power supply frequency.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p01] Devices such as industrial and domestic air conditioners, refrigerators, and heaters adjusted their duty cycle to avoid activation during times the grid was suffering a peak condition.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p01] Beginning in 2000, Italy's Telegestore Project was the first to network large numbers (27 million) of homes using smart meters connected via low bandwidth power line communication.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p01] Some experiments used the term broadband over power lines (BPL), while others used wireless technologies such as mesh networking promoted for more reliable connections to disparate devices in the home as well as supporting metering of other utilities such as gas and water.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p01] Monitoring and synchronization of wide-area networks were revolutionized in the early 1990s when the Bonneville Power Administration expanded its smart grid research with prototype sensors that are capable of very rapid analysis of anomalies in electricity quality over very large geographic areas.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p01] The culmination of this work was the first operational Wide Area Measurement System (WAMS) in 2000.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p01] Other countries are rapidly integrating this technology — China started having a comprehensive national WAMS when the past 5-year economic plan was completed in 2012.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p01] The earliest deployments of smart grids include the Italian system *Telegestore* (2005), the mesh network of Austin, Texas (since 2003), and the smart grid in Boulder, Colorado (2008).
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p01] See § Deployments and attempted deployments below.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p01] A smart grid would allow the power industry to observe and control parts of the system at higher resolution in time and space.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p01] One of the purposes of the smart grid is real time information exchange to make operation as efficient as possible.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p01] It would allow management of the grid on all time scales from high-frequency switching devices on a microsecond scale, to wind and solar output variations on a minute scale, to the future effects of the carbon emissions generated by power production on a decade scale.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p01] Because of the diverse range of factors, there are numerous competing taxonomies and no agreement on a universal definition.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p01] Nevertheless, one possible categorization is given here.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p01] The smart grid makes use of technologies such as state estimation, that improve fault detection and allow self-healing of the network without the intervention of technicians.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p01] This will ensure a more reliable supply of electricity and reduce vulnerability to natural disasters or attacks.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p01] Although multiple routes are touted as a feature of the smart grid, the old grid also featured multiple routes.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p01] Initial power lines in the grid were built using a radial model, later connectivity was guaranteed via multiple routes, referred to as a network structure.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p01] However, this created a new problem: if the current flow or related effects across the network exceed the limits of any particular network element, it could fail, and the current would be shunted to other network elements, which eventually may fail also, causing a domino effect.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p01] A technique to prevent this is load shedding by rolling blackout or voltage reduction (brownout).
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p01] Classic grids were designed for a one-way flow of electricity, but if a local sub-network generates more power than it is consuming, the reverse flow can raise safety and reliability issues.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p01] A smart grid aims to manage these situations.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p01] The overall effect is less redundancy in transmission and distribution lines, and greater utilization of generators, leading to lower power prices.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p01] The total load connected to the power grid can vary significantly over time.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p01] Although the total load is the sum of many individual choices of the clients, the overall load is not necessarily stable or slow varying.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p01] For example, if a popular television program starts, millions of televisions will start to draw current instantly.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p01] Traditionally, to respond to a rapid increase in power consumption, faster than the start-up time of a large generator, some spare generators are put on a dissipative standby mode.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p01] A smart grid may warn all individual television sets, or another larger customer, to reduce the load temporarily (to allow time to start up a larger generator) or continuously (in the case of limited resources).
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p01] Using mathematical prediction algorithms it is possible to predict how many standby generators need to be used, to reach a certain failure rate.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p01] In the traditional grid, the failure rate can only be reduced at the cost of more standby generators.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p01] In a smart grid, the load reduction by even a small portion of the clients may eliminate the problem.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p01] To reduce demand during the high-cost peak usage periods, communications and metering technologies inform smart devices in the home and business when energy demand is high and track how much electricity is used and when it is used.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p01] It also gives utility companies the ability to reduce consumption by communicating to devices directly in order to prevent system overloads.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p01] Examples would be a utility reducing the usage of a group of electric vehicle charging stations or shifting temperature set points of air conditioners in a city.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p01] To motivate them to cut back use and perform what is called **peak curtailment** or **peak leveling**, prices of electricity are increased during high demand periods and decreased during low demand periods.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p01] It is thought that consumers and businesses will tend to consume less during high-demand periods if it is possible for consumers and consumer devices to be aware of the high price premium for using electricity at peak periods.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p01] This could mean making trade-offs such as cycling on/off air conditioners or running dishwashers at 9 pm instead of 5 pm.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p01] When businesses and consumers see a direct economic benefit of using energy at off-peak times, the theory is that they will include the energy cost of operation into their consumer device and building construction decisions and hence become more energy efficient.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p01] Current network infrastructure is not built to allow for many distributed feed-in points, and typically even if some feed-in is allowed at the local (distribution) level, the transmission-level infrastructure cannot accommodate it.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p01] Rapid fluctuations in distributed generation, such as due to cloudy or gusty weather, present significant challenges to power engineers who need to ensure stable power levels through varying the output of the more controllable generators such as gas turbines and hydroelectric generators.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p01] Smart grid technology is a necessary condition for very large amounts of renewable electricity on the grid for this reason.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p01] There is also support for vehicle-to-grid.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p01] The smart grid allows for systematic communication between suppliers (their energy price) and consumers (their willingness-to-pay), and permits both the suppliers and the consumers to be more flexible and sophisticated in their operational strategies.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p01] Only the critical loads will need to pay the peak energy prices, and consumers will be able to be more strategic in when they use energy.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p01] Generators with greater flexibility will be able to sell energy strategically for maximum profit, whereas inflexible generators such as base-load steam turbines and wind turbines will receive a varying tariff based on the level of demand and the status of the other generators currently operating.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p01] The overall effect is a signal that awards energy efficiency, and energy consumption that is sensitive to the time-varying limitations of the supply.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p01] At the domestic level, appliances with a degree of energy storage or thermal mass (such as refrigerators, heat banks, and heat pumps) will be well placed to 'play' the market and seek to minimise energy cost by adapting demand to the lower-cost energy support periods.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p01] This is an extension of the dual-tariff energy pricing mentioned above.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p01] Demand response support allows generators and loads to interact in an automated fashion in real-time, coordinating demand to flatten spikes.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p01] Eliminating the fraction of demand that occurs in these spikes eliminates the cost of adding reserve generators, cuts wear and tear and extends the life of equipment, and allows users to cut their energy bills by telling low priority devices to use energy only when it is cheapest.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p01] Currently, power grid systems have varying degrees of communication within control systems for their high-value assets, such as in generating plants, transmission lines, substations, and major energy users.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p01] In general, information flows one way, from the users and the loads they control back to the utilities.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p01] The utilities attempt to meet the demand and succeed or fail to varying degrees (brownouts, rolling blackout, uncontrolled blackout).
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p01] The total amount of power demanded by the users can have a very wide probability distribution which requires spare generating plants in standby mode to respond to the rapidly changing power usage.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p01] This one-way flow of information is expensive; the last 10% of generating capacity may be required as little as 1% of the time, and brownouts and outages can be costly to consumers.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p01] Demand response can be provided by commercial, residential loads, and industrial loads.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p01] For example, Alcoa's Warrick Operation is participating in MISO as a qualified Demand Response Resource, and the Trimet Aluminium uses its smelter as a short-term mega-battery.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p01] Latency of the data flow is a major concern, with some early smart meter architectures allowing actually as long as 24 hours delay in receiving the data, preventing any possible reaction by either supplying or demanding devices.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p01] The bulk of smart grid technologies are already used in other applications such as manufacturing and telecommunications and are being adapted for use in grid operations.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p01] Many different concepts have been used to model intelligent power grids.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p01] They are generally studied within the framework of complex systems.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p01] In a recent brainstorming session, the power grid was considered within the context of optimal control, ecology, human cognition, glassy dynamics, information theory, microphysics of clouds, and many others.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p01] Here is a selection of the types of analyses that have appeared in recent years.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p01] Evans in their study introduced the concept of a substation based smart protection and hybrid Inspection Unit.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p01] The power grid has been mapped onto variations of the Kuramoto model, a well-studied framework for synchronization of nonlinear oscillators.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p01] The model describes how the electrical system keeps the power balance, to maintain phase synchronization (also known as phase locking).
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p01] Strictly speaking, the model is most used for an ordinary electrical grid, to determine, for instance, the role of branch insertions or of parameters dispersion.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p01] Non-uniform oscillators also help to model different technologies, different types of power generators, patterns of consumption, and so on.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p01] The model has also been used to describe the synchronization patterns in the blinking of fireflies.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p01] Network Simulators are used to simulate/emulate network communication effects.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p01] This typically involves setting up a lab with the smart grid devices, applications etc. with the virtual network being provided by the network simulator.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p01] Neural networks have been considered for power grid management as well.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p01] Electric power systems can be classified in multiple different ways: non-linear, dynamic, discrete, or random.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p01] Artificial Neural Networks (ANNs) attempt to solve the most difficult of these problems, the non-linear problems.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p01] One application of ANNs is in demand forecasting.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p01] In order for grids to operate economically and reliably, demand forecasting is essential, because it is used to predict the amount of power that will be consumed by the load.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p01] This is dependent on weather conditions, type of day, random events, incidents, etc.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p01] For non-linear loads though, the load profile isn't smooth and as predictable, resulting in higher uncertainty and less accuracy using the traditional Artificial Intelligence models.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p01] An example of the last case would be given the type of day, whether its weekday or weekend, that wouldn't have much of an effect on Hospital grids, but it'd be a big factor in resident housing grids' load profile.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p01] As wind power continues to gain popularity, it becomes a necessary ingredient in realistic power grid studies.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p01] Off-line storage, wind variability, supply, demand, pricing, and other factors can be modelled as a mathematical game.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p01] Here the goal is to develop a winning strategy.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p01] Markov processes have been used to model and study this type of system.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p01] In 2009, the US smart grid industry was valued at about $21.4 billion – by 2014, it will exceed at least $42.8 billion.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p01] Given the success of the smart grids in the U.S., the world market is expected to grow at a faster rate, surging from $69.3 billion in 2009 to $171.4 billion by 2014.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p01] With the segments set to benefit the most will be smart metering hardware sellers and makers of software used to transmit and organize the massive amount of data collected by meters.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p01] A 2011 study from the Electric Power Research Institute concludes that investment in a U.S. smart grid will cost up to $476 billion over 20 years but will provide up to $2 trillion in customer benefits over that time.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p01] A 2019 study from International Energy Agency estimates that the current (depreciated) value of the US electric grid is more than US$1 trillion.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p01] The total cost of replacing it with a smart grid is estimated to be more than US$4 trillion.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p01] If smart grids are deployed fully across the US, the country expects to save US$130 billion annually.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p01] As customers can choose their electricity suppliers, depending on their different tariff methods, the focus of transportation costs will be increased.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p01] Reduction of maintenance and replacements costs will stimulate more advanced control.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p01] A 2003 United States Department of Energy study calculated that internal modernization of US grids with smart grid capabilities would save between 46 and 117 billion dollars over the next 20 years if implemented within a few years of the study.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p01] As well as these industrial modernization benefits, smart grid features could expand energy efficiency beyond the grid into the home by coordinating low priority home devices such as water heaters so that their use of power takes advantage of the most desirable energy sources.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p01] Smart grids can also coordinate the production of power from large numbers of small power producers such as owners of rooftop solar panels — an arrangement that would otherwise prove problematic for power systems operators at local utilities.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p01] One important question is whether consumers will act in response to market signals.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p01] Another concern is that the cost of telecommunications to fully support smart grids may be prohibitive.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p01] A less expensive communication mechanism is proposed using a form of "dynamic demand management" where devices shave peaks by shifting their loads in reaction to grid frequency.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p01] Grid frequency could be used to communicate load information without the need of an additional telecommunication network, but it would not support economic bargaining or quantification of contributions.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p01] Although there are specific and proven smart grid technologies in use, *smart grid* is an aggregate term for a set of related technologies on which a specification is generally agreed, rather than a name for a specific technology.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p01] The increased efficiency and reliability of the smart grid is expected to save consumers money and help reduce CO2 emissions.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] Most opposition and concerns have centered on smart meters and the items (such as remote control, remote disconnect, and variable rate pricing) enabled by them.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] Where opposition to smart meters is encountered, they are often marketed as "smart grid" which connects smart grid to smart meters in the eyes of opponents.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] While modernization of electrical grids into smart grids allows for optimization of everyday processes, a smart grid, being online, can be vulnerable to cyberattacks.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] Transformers which increase the voltage of electricity created at power plants for long-distance travel, transmission lines themselves, and distribution lines which deliver the electricity to its consumers are particularly susceptible.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] These systems rely on sensors which gather information from the field and then deliver it to control centers, where algorithms automate analysis and decision-making processes.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] These decisions are sent back to the field, where existing equipment execute them.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] Hackers have the potential to disrupt these automated control systems, severing the channels which allow generated electricity to be utilized.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] This is called a denial of service or DoS attack.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] They can also launch integrity attacks which corrupt information being transmitted along the system as well as desynchronization attacks which affect when such information is delivered to the appropriate location.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] Additionally, intruders can gain access via renewable energy generation systems and smart meters connected to the grid, taking advantage of more specialized weaknesses or ones whose security has not been prioritized.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] Because a smart grid has a large number of access points, like smart meters, defending all of its weak points can prove difficult.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] Advanced Persistent Threats (APTs) have evolved to target smart grids by reprogramming Programmable Logic Controllers (PLCs) to display false 'normal' operating conditions to operators while causing physical damage.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] To counter these vulnerabilities, experts recommend shifting from traditional network segmentation to 'micro-segmentation' and adopting 'zero-trust' models that require verification at every layer of the infrastructure.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] There is also concern on the security of the infrastructure, primarily that involving communications technology.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] Concerns chiefly center around the communications technology at the heart of the smart grid.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] Designed to allow real-time contact between utilities and meters in customers' homes and businesses, there is a risk that these capabilities could be exploited for criminal or even terrorist actions.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] One of the key capabilities of this connectivity is the ability to remotely switch off power supplies, enabling utilities to quickly and easily cease or modify supplies to customers who default on payment.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] This is undoubtedly a massive boon for energy providers, but also raises some significant security issues.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] Cybercriminals have infiltrated the U.S. electric grid before on numerous occasions.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] Aside from computer infiltration, there are also concerns that computer malware like Stuxnet, which targeted SCADA systems which are widely used in industry, could be used to attack a smart grid network.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] Electricity theft is a concern in the U.S. where the smart meters being deployed use RF technology to communicate with the electricity transmission network.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] People with knowledge of electronics can devise interference devices to cause the smart meter to report lower than actual usage.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] Similarly, the same technology can be employed to make it appear that the energy the consumer is using is being used by another customer, increasing their bill.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] The damage from a well-executed, sizable cyberattack could be extensive and long-lasting.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] One incapacitated substation could take from nine days to over a year to repair, depending on the nature of the attack.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] It can also cause an hours-long outage in a small radius.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] It could have an immediate effect on transportation infrastructure, as traffic lights and other routing mechanisms as well as ventilation equipment for underground roadways is reliant on electricity.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] Additionally, infrastructure which relies on the electric grid, including wastewater treatment facilities, the information technology sector, and communications systems could be impacted.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] The December 2015 Ukraine power grid cyberattack, the first recorded of its kind, disrupted services to nearly a quarter of a million people by bringing substations offline.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] The Council on Foreign Relations has noted that states are most likely to be the perpetrators of such an attack as they have access to the resources to carry one out despite the high level of difficulty of doing so.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] Cyber intrusions can be used as portions of a larger offensive, military or otherwise.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] Some security experts warn that this type of event is easily scalable to grids elsewhere.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] Insurance company Lloyd's of London has already modeled the outcome of a cyberattack on the Eastern Interconnection, which has the potential to impact 15 states, put 93 million people in the dark, and cost the country's economy anywhere from $243 billion to $1 trillion in various damages.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] House of Representatives Subcommittee on Economic Development, Public Buildings, and Emergency Management, the electric grid has already seen a sizable number of cyber intrusions, with two in every five aiming to incapacitate it.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] Department of Energy has prioritized research and development to decrease the electric grid's vulnerability to cyberattacks, citing them as an "imminent danger" in its 2017 Quadrennial Energy Review.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] The Department of Energy has also identified both attack resistance and self-healing as major keys to ensuring that today's smart grid is future-proof.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] While there are regulations already in place, namely the Critical Infrastructure Protection Standards introduced by the North America Electric Reliability Council, a significant number of them are suggestions rather than mandates.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] Most electricity generation, transmission, and distribution facilities and equipment are owned by private stakeholders, further complicating the task of assessing adherence to such standards.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] Additionally, even if utilities want to fully comply, they may find that it is too expensive to do so.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] Some experts argue that the first step to increasing the cyber defenses of the smart electric grid is completing a comprehensive risk analysis of existing infrastructure, including research of software, hardware, and communication processes.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] Additionally, as intrusions themselves can provide valuable information, it could be useful to analyze system logs and other records of their nature and timing.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] Common weaknesses already identified using such methods by the Department of Homeland Security include poor code quality, improper authentication, and weak firewall rules.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] Once this step is completed, some suggest that it makes sense to then complete an analysis of the potential consequences of the aforementioned failures or shortcomings.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] This includes both immediate consequences as well as second- and third-order cascading effects on parallel systems.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] Finally, risk mitigation solutions, which may include simple remediation of infrastructure inadequacies or novel strategies, can be deployed to address the situation.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] Some such measures include recoding of control system algorithms to make them more able to resist and recover from cyberattacks or preventive techniques that allow more efficient detection of unusual or unauthorized changes to data.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] Strategies to account for human error which can compromise systems include educating those who work in the field to be wary of strange USB drives, which can introduce malware if inserted, even if just to check their contents.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] Other solutions include utilizing transmission substations, constrained SCADA networks, policy based data sharing, and attestation for constrained smart meters.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] Transmission substations utilize one-time signature authentication technologies and one-way hash chain constructs.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] These constraints have since been remedied with the creation of a fast-signing and verification technology and buffering-free data processing.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] A similar solution has been constructed for constrained SCADA networks.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] This involves applying a Hash-Based Message Authentication Code to byte streams, converting the random-error detection available on legacy systems to a mechanism that guarantees data authenticity.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] Policy-based data sharing utilizes GPS-clock-synchronized-fine-grain power grid measurements to provide increased grid stability and reliability.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] It does this through synchro-phasor requirements that are gathered by PMUs.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] Attestation for constrained smart meters faces a slightly different challenge, however.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] One of the biggest issues with attestation for constrained smart meters is that in order to prevent energy theft, and similar attacks, cyber security providers have to make sure that the devices' software is authentic.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] To combat this problem, an architecture for constrained smart networks has been created and implemented at a low level in the embedded system.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] The protection system of a smart grid provides grid reliability analysis, failure protection, and security and privacy protection services.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] While the additional communication infrastructure of a smart grid provides additional protective and security mechanisms, it also presents a risk of external attack and internal failures.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] Before a utility installs an advanced metering system, or any type of smart system, it must make a business case for the investment.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] Some components, like the power system stabilizers (PSS) installed on generators are very expensive, require complex integration in the grid's control system, are needed only during emergencies, and are only effective if other suppliers on the network have them.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] Without any incentive to install them, power suppliers don't.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] Most utilities find it difficult to justify installing a communications infrastructure for a single application (e.g. meter reading).
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] Because of this, a utility must typically identify several applications that will use the same communications infrastructure – for example, reading a meter, monitoring power quality, remote connection and disconnection of customers, enabling demand response, etc.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] Ideally, the communications infrastructure will not only support near-term applications, but unanticipated applications that will arise in the future.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] Regulatory or legislative actions can also drive utilities to implement pieces of a smart grid puzzle.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] Each utility has a unique set of business, regulatory, and legislative drivers that guide its investments.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] This means that each utility will take a different path to creating their smart grid and that different utilities will create smart grids at different adoption rates.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] Some features of smart grids draw opposition from industries that currently are, or hope to provide similar services.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] An example is competition with cable and DSL Internet providers from broadband over powerline internet access.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] Providers of SCADA control systems for grids have intentionally designed proprietary hardware, protocols and software so that they cannot inter-operate with other systems in order to tie its customers to the vendor.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] The incorporation of digital communications and computer infrastructure with the grid's existing physical infrastructure poses challenges and inherent vulnerabilities.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] According to *IEEE Security & Privacy*, the smart grid will require that people develop and use large computer and communication infrastructure that supports a greater degree of situational awareness and that allows for more specific command and control operations.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] This process is necessary to support major systems such as demand-response wide-area measurement and control, storage and transportation of electricity, and the automation of electric distribution.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] Various "smart grid" systems have dual functions.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] This includes Advanced Metering Infrastructure systems which, when used with various software can be used to detect power theft and by process of elimination, detect where equipment failures have taken place.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] These are in addition to their primary functions of eliminating the need for human meter reading and measuring the time-of-use of electricity.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] The worldwide power loss including theft is estimated at two-hundred billion dollars annually.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] Electricity theft also represents a major challenge when providing reliable electrical service in developing countries.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] The earliest, and one of the largest, example of a smart grid is the Italian system installed by Enel S.p.A. of Italy.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] Completed in 2005, the Telegestore project was highly unusual in the utility world because the company designed and manufactured their own meters, acted as their own system integrator, and developed their own system software.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] The Telegestore project is widely regarded as the first commercial scale use of smart grid technology to the home, and delivers annual savings of 500 million euro at a project cost of 2.1 billion euro.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] One of the largest deployment programs in the world to-date is the U.S.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] Dept. of Energy's Smart Grid Program funded by the American Recovery and Reinvestment Act of 2009.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] This program required matching funding from individual utilities.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] A total of over $9 billion in Public/Private funds were invested as part of this program.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] This program consisted of Investment Grants (matching), Demonstration Projects, Consumer Acceptance Studies, and Workforce Education Programs.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] Reports from all individual utility programs as well as overall impact reports will be completed by the second quarter of 2015.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] In the U.S., the Energy Policy Act of 2005 and Title XIII of the Energy Independence and Security Act of 2007 are providing funding to encourage smart grid development.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] The objective is to enable utilities to better predict their needs, and in some cases involve consumers in a time-of-use tariff.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] Funds have also been allocated to develop more robust energy control technologies.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] In the US, the city of Austin, Texas, has been working on building its smart grid since 2003, when its utility first replaced 1/3 of its manual meters with smart meters that communicate via a wireless mesh network.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] It currently manages 200,000 devices real-time (smart meters, smart thermostats, and sensors across its service area), and expects to be supporting 500,000 devices real-time in 2009 servicing 1 million consumers and 43,000 businesses.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] Boulder, Colorado, completed the first phase of its smart grid project in August 2008.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] Both systems use the smart meter as a gateway to the home automation network (HAN) that controls smart sockets and devices.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] Some HAN designers favor decoupling control functions from the meter, out of concern of future mismatches with new standards and technologies available from the fast moving business segment of home electronic devices.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] Hydro One, in Ontario, Canada is in the midst of a large-scale Smart Grid initiative, deploying a standards-compliant communications infrastructure from Trilliant.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] By the end of 2010, the system will serve 1.3 million customers in the province of Ontario.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] The initiative won the "Best AMR Initiative in North America" award from the Utility Planning Network.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] Île d'Yeu began a 2-year pilot program in Spring of 2020.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] Twenty-three houses in the Ker Pissot neighborhood and surrounding areas were interconnected with a microgrid that was automated as a smart grid with software from Engie.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] Sixty-four solar panels with a peak capacity of 23.7 kW were installed on five houses and a battery with a storage capacity of 15 kWh was installed on one house.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] Six houses store excess solar energy in their hot water heaters.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] A dynamic system apportions the energy provided by the solar panels and stored in the battery and hot water heaters to the system of 23 houses.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] The smart grid software dynamically updates energy supply and demand in 5 minute intervals, deciding whether to pull energy from the battery or from the panels and when to store it in the hot water heaters.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] This pilot program was the first such project in France.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] The City of Mannheim in Germany is using realtime Broadband Powerline (BPL) communications in its Model City Mannheim "MoMa" project.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] Sydney also in Australia, in partnership with the Australian Government implemented the Smart Grid, Smart City program.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] It will be possible to control and manage the state of the entire electricity distribution grid at any given instant, allowing suppliers and energy services companies to use this technological platform to offer consumers information and added-value energy products and services.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] This project to install an intelligent energy grid places Portugal and EDP at the cutting edge of technological innovation and service provision in Europe.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] In the so-called *E-Energy* projects several German utilities are creating first nucleolus in six independent model regions.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] A technology competition identified this model regions to carry out research and development activities with the main objective to create an "Internet of Energy".
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] One of the first attempted deployments of "smart grid" technologies in the United States was rejected in 2009 by electricity regulators in the Commonwealth of Massachusetts, a US state.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] This plan was rejected by regulators as it "eroded important protections for low-income customers against shutoffs".
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] According to the Boston Globe, the plan "unfairly targeted low-income customers and circumvented Massachusetts laws meant to help struggling consumers keep the lights on".
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] In the Netherlands a large-scale project (>5000 connections, >20 partners) was initiated to demonstrate integrated smart grids technologies, services and business cases.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] EPB in Chattanooga, TN is a municipally owned electric utility that started construction of a smart grid in 2008, receiving a $111,567,606 grant from the US DOE in 2009 to expedite construction and implementation (for a total budget of $232,219,350).
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] Deployment of power-line interrupters (1170 units) was completed in April 2012, and deployment of smart meters (172,079 units) was completed in 2013.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] The smart grid's backbone fiber-optic system was also used to provide the first gigabit-speed internet connection to residential customers in the US through the Fiber to the Home initiative, and now speeds of up to 10 gigabits per second are available to residents.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] The smart grid is estimated to have reduced power outages by an average of 60%, saving the city about 60 million dollars annually.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] It has also reduced the need for "truck rolls" to scout and troubleshoot faults, resulting in an estimated reduction of 630,000 truck driving miles, and 4.7 million pounds of carbon emissions.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] In January 2016, EPB became the first major power distribution system to earn Performance Excellence in Electricity Renewal (PEER) certification.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] Certain deployments utilize the OpenADR standard for load shedding and demand reduction during higher demand periods.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] The smart grid market in China is estimated to be $22.3 billion with a projected growth to $61.4 billion by 2015.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] Honeywell is developing a demand response pilot and feasibility study for China with the State Grid Corp. of China using the OpenADR demand response standard.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] The State Grid Corp., the Chinese Academy of Sciences, and General Electric intend to work together to develop standards for China's smart grid rollout.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] In 2009, the US Department of Energy awarded an $11 million grant to Southern California Edison and Honeywell for a demand response program that automatically turns down energy use during peak hours for participating industrial customers.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] The Department of Energy awarded an $11.4 million grant to Honeywell to implement the program using the OpenADR standard.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] (HECO) is implementing a two-year pilot project to test the ability of an ADR program to respond to the intermittence of wind power.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] Hawaii has a goal to obtain 70 percent of its power from renewable sources by 2030.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] HECO will give customers incentives for reducing power consumption within 10 minutes of a notice.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] Part of the IEEE Smart Grid Initiative, IEEE 2030.2 represents an extension of the work aimed at utility storage systems for transmission and distribution networks.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] The IEEE P2030 group expects to deliver early 2011 an overarching set of guidelines on smart grid interfaces.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] The new guidelines will cover areas including batteries and supercapacitors as well as flywheels.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] The group has also spun out a 2030.1 effort drafting guidelines for integrating electric vehicles into the smart grid.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] IEC TC 57 has created a family of international standards that can be used as part of the smart grid.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] These standards include IEC 61850 which is an architecture for substation automation, and IEC 61970/61968 – the Common Information Model (CIM).
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] The CIM provides for common semantics to be used for turning data into information.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] OpenADR is an open-source smart grid communications standard used for demand response applications.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] It is typically used to send information and signals to cause electrical power-using devices to be turned off during periods of higher demand.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] MultiSpeak has created a specification that supports distribution functionality of the smart grid.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] MultiSpeak has a robust set of integration definitions that supports nearly all of the software interfaces necessary for a distribution utility or for the distribution portion of a vertically integrated utility.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] MultiSpeak integration is defined using extensible markup language (XML) and web services.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] The IEEE has created a standard to support synchrophasors – C37.118.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] The UCA International User Group discusses and supports real world experience of the standards used in smart grids.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] A utility task group within LonMark International deals with smart grid related issues.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] There is a growing trend towards the use of TCP/IP technology as a common communication platform for smart meter applications, so that utilities can deploy multiple communication systems, while using IP technology as a common management platform.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] IEEE P2030 is an IEEE project developing a "Draft Guide for Smart Grid Interoperability of Energy Technology and Information Technology Operation with the Electric Power System (EPS), and End-Use Applications and Loads".
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] NIST has included ITU-T G.hn as one of the "Standards Identified for Implementation" for the Smart Grid "for which it believed there was strong stakeholder consensus".
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] G.hn is standard for high-speed communications over power lines, phone lines and coaxial cables.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] OASIS EnergyInterop' – An OASIS technical committee developing XML standards for energy interoperation.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] Its starting point is the California OpenADR standard.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] Under the Energy Independence and Security Act of 2007 (EISA), NIST is charged with overseeing the identification and selection of hundreds of standards that will be required to implement the Smart Grid in the U.S.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] These standards will be referred by NIST to the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission (FERC).
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] This work has begun, and the first standards have already been selected for inclusion in NIST's Smart Grid catalog.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] However, some commentators have suggested that the benefits that could be realized from Smart Grid standardization could be threatened by a growing number of patents that cover Smart Grid architecture and technologies.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] If patents that cover standardized Smart Grid elements are not revealed until technology is broadly distributed throughout the network ("locked-in"), significant disruption could occur when patent holders seek to collect unanticipated rents from large segments of the market.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] In November 2017 the non-profit GridWise Alliance along with Clean Edge Inc., a clean energy group, released rankings for all 50 states in their efforts to modernize the electric grid.
[src:demand-response/smart-grid-p02] The other top states were Illinois, Texas, Maryland, Oregon, Arizona, the District of Columbia, New York, Nevada and Delaware.
